[Category:Treaties of the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United States]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Vanuatu]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Zambia]]\n[[Category:1984 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Treaties adopted by United Nations General Assembly resolutions]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Anguilla]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the British Virgin Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Cayman Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Montserrat]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Pitcairn Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Netherlands Antilles]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Aruba]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Greenland]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to British Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Portuguese Macau]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Bermuda]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Jersey]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to West Berlin]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Committee_Against_Torture_(UN)"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on abortion in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|impact of COVID-19}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\nAs a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion. In the US, many nonessential medical procedures were temporarily suspended to preserve medical resources like [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE). Some Republican legislators specifically included abortion services as nonessential medical procedures, resulting in several legal challenges.<ref name=\"Gold\"/>\n\n==Alabama==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alabama}}\nOn March 20, an order was signed to prevent Alabama hospitals from performing elective medical procedures. The [[Alabama Department of Public Health]] initially stated that abortions providers were not affected by this order. An additional order on March 27 banned any medical procedure except those to treat an \"emergency medical condition\". The office of Alabama Attorney General [[Steve Marshall (politician)|Steve Marshall]] suggested that the state's three remaining abortion clinics could be prosecuted for performing procedures on grounds of the March 27 order, causing the clinics to seek a [[temporary restraining order]]. On March 30, U.S. District Judge [[Myron Thompson]] decided on a temporary restraining order, saying the attorney general's interpretation of the March 27 order was overly broad, potentially causing [[undue burden]] on abortion access.<ref>{{cite news |first=Bryan |last=Lyman |url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/2020/03/30/coronavirus-federal-judge-blocks-alabama-attempt-stop-abortions-during-outbreak/5091465002/ |title=Coronavirus: Federal judge rules abortion procedures can continue during outbreak |date=March 30, 2020 |work=Montgomery Advertiser |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Iowa==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iowa}}\nGovernor [[Kim Reynolds]] included abortion as a nonessential medical procedure and temporarily banned it in response to the pandemic. However, Iowa Solicitor General Jeffrey Thompson later \"acknowledged that when determining whether a surgical abortion can be delayed without undue risk to the woman, there also should be consideration of other medical factors \u2014 like whether the timing of the patient's pregnancy would prevent the woman from obtaining a legal abortion after the directive expires\".<ref name=\"Mehaffey\"/> The statement was seen as a clarification that Iowa was not actually seeking to temporarily ban all surgical abortions.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> Abortion clinics in Iowa, which had filed for an emergency injunction, dropped their request. [[Planned Parenthood]] announced that it \"will resume seeing patients for in-clinic procedures, in compliance with Gov. Kim Reynolds' proclamation\", while Governor Reynolds was said to be \"pleased that her proclamation remains in full effect and that surgical abortions will not be exempted from this suspension of non-essential and elective surgeries\".<ref name=\"Mehaffey\">{{cite news |first=Trish |last=Mehaffey |url=https://muscatinejournal.com/news/state-and-regional/iowa/abortion-clinics-won-t-contest-covid-19-order/article_3acb7d22-c07c-5f95-a4d7-ebe690344e3e.html |title=Abortion clinics won't contest COVID-19 order |work=Muscadine Journal|date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Mississippi==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi}}\nIn March, a Mississippi directive to temporarily ban elective, non-essential medical procedures went into effect. Governor [[Tate Reeves]] said he would enact \"whatever action we need to to protect the not only the lives of unborn children, but also the lives of anyone who may contract this particular virus\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/abortion-ban-mississippi-governor-tate-reeves-coronavirus/ |title=Mississippi Governor Tate Reeves calls for abortion ban during coronavirus outbreak |first=Kate |last=Smith |date=March 25, 2020 |publisher=CBS News |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The lone abortion clinic in Mississippi, operated by the [[Center for Reproductive Rights]], confirmed that its clinic was still open and performing procedures.<ref name=\"Gold\"/>\n\n==Ohio==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio}}\nOn March 17, Director of the [[Ohio Department of Health]] [[Amy Acton]] issued an order prohibiting nonessential surgeries to preserve [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE).<ref name=\"Rowland\">{{cite news |first=Darrel |last= Rowland |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200405/capitol-insider--ohio-stance-on-abortion-during-coronavirus-crisis-made-clear-in-court-filing |title=Ohio stance on abortion during coronavirus crisis made clear in court filing |work=The Columbus Dispatch |date=April 5, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Governor [[Mike DeWine]] said abortions should not be performed during the pandemic except when the pregnant person's life is at risk.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew J. |last=Tobias |url=https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/03/federal-judge-blocks-ohio-from-using-coronavirus-health-order-to-restrict-abortions.html |title=Federal judge blocks Ohio from using coronavirus health order to restrict abortions |date=March 30, 2020 |website=The Plain Dealer |location=Cleveland |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Deputy Attorney General Jonathan Fulkerson sent letters to three abortion providers to compel them to comply with the state ban on nonessential medical procedures. Two clinics announced that abortions were necessary medical procedures, and thus they would continue to provide them. District Court judge Michael Barrett ruled in favor of Planned Parenthood on April 1, ordering a two week suspension of the ban.<ref name=\"Gold\">{{cite news |first=Hannah |last=Gold |date=April 7, 2020 |url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/04/every-state-thats-tried-to-ban-abortion-over-coronavirus.html |title=Every State That's Tried to Ban Abortion Over the Coronavirus |website=The Cut |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The State of Ohio appealed Barrett's decision and asked him to put a hold on his order until the appeal was decided, which he declined to do. The state's abortion providers are represented by attorneys from the ACLU, Planned Parenthood, the ACLU of Ohio, and the Cincinnati firm [[Al Gerhardstein|Gerhardstein]] & Branch Co. [[Amicus curiae|Friend of the court]] briefs were filed by the Republican Attorneys General of fifteen states, including neighboring Kentucky, Indiana, and West Virginia, in support of Ohio's efforts to restrict abortion during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Edwards Baker |publisher=WXIX-TV |location=Cincinnati |url=https://www.fox19.com/2020/04/02/ohio-appeals-order-allowing-abortions-during-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=Ohio appeals order allowing abortions during coronavirus pandemic |date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> State of Ohio Attorney General [[Dave Yost]] later clarified that all [[medical abortions]] were still allowed, and that \"doctors remain free to perform surgical abortions necessary for a mother's health or life, and also surgical abortions that cannot be delayed without jeopardizing the patient's abortion rights.\"<ref name=\"Rowland\"/> On April 6, the State's request for an appeal was dismissed by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.statenews.org/post/court-refuses-overrule-ruling-stops-ohio-closing-abortion-clinics|title=Court Refuses To Overrule Ruling That Stops Ohio From Closing Abortion Clinics|website=Statehouse News Bureau |first=Jo |last=Ingles|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Oklahoma==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oklahoma}}\nIn March, Governor [[Kevin Stitt]] signed an executive order to limit elective medical procedures, later confirming that all types of abortion services were included, except for those necessary in a medical emergency or to \"prevent serious health risks\" to the pregnant person. On April 6, federal judge [[Charles Barnes Goodwin]] blocked the executive order, ruling that the state acted in an arbitrary, unreasonable, and oppressive way, which posed an undue burden on abortion access in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/06/politics/oklahoma-abortion-block-coronavirus/index.html |title=Oklahoma judge blocks state order restricting abortion during coronavirus outbreak |first=Caroline |last=Kelly |date=April 6, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Texas==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas}}\nIn Texas, Governor [[Greg Abbott]] issued an executive order on March 22 that temporarily banned elective medical procedures. Attorney General [[Ken Paxton]] warned on March 23 that all abortions were now prohibited, except those necessary to \"preserve the life or health\" of the pregnant person.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> Those found in violation of the ban could be fined up to $1,000, jailed for 180 days, and have their medical license revoked.<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref name=\"Chung\"/> U.S. District Judge [[Lee Yeakel]] ruled in favor of the clinics on March 26, saying that the temporary ban on abortions \"prevents Texas women from exercising what the Supreme Court has declared is their fundamental constitutional right to terminate a pregnancy before a fetus is viable\".<ref name=\"Chung\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-abortion/u-s-judge-stops-texas-from-curbing-abortions-during-coronavirus-crisis-idUSKBN21H3B1 |title=U.S. judges stop Texas, Ohio, Alabama from curbing abortions during coronavirus crisis |first=Andrew |last=Chung |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Reuters |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> This ruling was overturned on March 31, 2020, when the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] allowed Texas to reinstate the ban.<ref name=\"Stern\">{{cite news |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/fifth-circuit-texas-coronavirus-abortion-ban.html |title=Federal Appeals Court Lets Texas Resume Abortion Ban |first=Mark Joseph |last= Stern |date=March 31, 2020 |website=Slate |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:Abortion in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Consequences of events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|impact of COVID-19}}\nAs a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion. In the US, many nonessential medical procedures were temporarily suspended to preserve medical resources like [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE). Some Republican legislators specifically included abortion services as nonessential medical procedures, resulting in several legal challenges.<ref name=\"Gold\"/>\n\n==Alabama==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alabama}}\nOn March 20, an order was signed to prevent Alabama hospitals from performing elective medical procedures. The [[Alabama Department of Public Health]] initially stated that abortions providers were not affected by this order. An additional order on March 27 banned any medical procedure except those to treat an \"emergency medical condition\". The office of Alabama Attorney General [[Steve Marshall (politician)|Steve Marshall]] suggested that the state's three remaining abortion clinics could be prosecuted for performing procedures on grounds of the March 27 order, causing the clinics to seek a [[temporary restraining order]]. On March 30, U.S. District Judge [[Myron Thompson]] decided on a temporary restraining order, saying the attorney general's interpretation of the March 27 order was overly broad, potentially causing [[undue burden]] on abortion access.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/2020/03/30/coronavirus-federal-judge-blocks-alabama-attempt-stop-abortions-during-outbreak/5091465002/| title=Coronavirus: Federal judge rules abortion procedures can continue during outbreak| date=30 March 2020| access-date=7 April 2020 | first=Bryan| last=Lyman}}</ref>\n\n==Iowa==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iowa}}\nGovernor [[Kim Reynolds]] included abortion as a nonessential medical procedure and temporarily banned it in response to the pandemic. However, Iowa Solicitor General Jeffrey Thompson later \"acknowledged that when determining whether a surgical abortion can be delayed without undue risk to the woman, there also should be consideration of other medical factors \u2014 like whether the timing of the patient's pregnancy would prevent the woman from obtaining a legal abortion after the directive expires\".<ref name=\"Mehaffey\"/> The statement was seen as a clarification that Iowa was not actually seeking to temporarily ban all surgical abortions.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> Abortion clinics in Iowa, which had filed for an emergency injunction, dropped their request. [[Planned Parenthood]] announced that it \"will resume seeing patients for in-clinic procedures, in compliance with Gov. Kim Reynolds\u2019 proclamation\", while Governor Reynolds was said to be \"pleased that her proclamation remains in full effect and that surgical abortions will not be exempted from this suspension of non-essential and elective surgeries\".<ref name=\"Mehaffey\">{{cite news|url=https://muscatinejournal.com/news/state-and-regional/iowa/abortion-clinics-won-t-contest-covid-19-order/article_3acb7d22-c07c-5f95-a4d7-ebe690344e3e.html| title=Abortion clinics won\u2019t contest COVID-19 order | work=Muscadine Journal|date=2 April 2020| access-date=7 April 2020| first=Trish| last=Mehaffey}}</ref>\n\n==Mississippi==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi}}\nIn March, a Mississippi directive to temporarily ban elective, non-essential medical procedures went into effect. Governor [[Tate Reeves]] said he would enact \"whatever action we need to to protect the not only the lives of unborn children, but also the lives of anyone who may contract this particular virus\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/abortion-ban-mississippi-governor-tate-reeves-coronavirus/| title=Mississippi Governor Tate Reeves calls for abortion ban during coronavirus outbreak| first=Kate| last=Smith| date=25 March 2020| access-date=7 April 2020| website=CBS News}}</ref> The lone abortion clinic in Mississippi, operated by the [[Center for Reproductive Rights]], confirmed that its clinic was still open and performing procedures.<ref name=\"Gold\"/>\n\n==Ohio==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio}}\nOn March 17, Director of the [[Ohio Department of Health]] [[Amy Acton]] issued an order prohibiting nonessential surgeries to preserve [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE).<ref name=\"Rowland\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200405/capitol-insider--ohio-stance-on-abortion-during-coronavirus-crisis-made-clear-in-court-filing| title=Ohio stance on abortion during coronavirus crisis made clear in court filing| work=The Columbus Dispatch| date=5 April 2020| access-date=7 April 2020| first=Darrel| last= Rowland}}</ref> Governor [[Mike DeWine]] said abortions should not be performed during the pandemic except when the pregnant person's life is at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/03/federal-judge-blocks-ohio-from-using-coronavirus-health-order-to-restrict-abortions.html| title=Federal judge blocks Ohio from using coronavirus health order to restrict abortions | date=30 March 2020| access-date=7 April 2020| website=Cleveland.com| first=Andrew J.| last=Tobias}}</ref> Deputy Attorney General Jonathan Fulkerson sent letters to three abortion providers to compel them to comply with the state ban on nonessential medical procedures. Two clinics announced that abortions were necessary medical procedures, and thus they would continue to provide them. District Court judge Michael Barrett ruled in favor of Planned Parenthood on April 1, ordering a two week suspension of the ban.<ref name=\"Gold\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/04/every-state-thats-tried-to-ban-abortion-over-coronavirus.html| title=Every State That\u2019s Tried to Ban Abortion Over the Coronavirus| website=The Cut| access-date=7 April 2020| first=Hannah| last=Gold| date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The State of Ohio appealed Barrett's decision and asked him to put a hold on his order until the appeal was decided, which he declined to do. The state's abortion providers are represented by attorneys from the ACLU, Planned Parenthood, the ACLU of Ohio, and the Cincinnati firm [[Al Gerhardstein|Gerhardstein]] & Branch Co. [[Amicus curiae|Friend of the court]] briefs were filed by the Republican Attorneys General of fifteen states, including neighboring Kentucky, Indiana, and West Virginia, in support of Ohio's efforts to restrict abortion during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.fox19.com/2020/04/02/ohio-appeals-order-allowing-abortions-during-coronavirus-pandemic/| title=Ohio appeals order allowing abortions during coronavirus pandemic| date=2 April 2020| access-date=7 April 2020| first=Jennifer| last=Edwards Baker| work=Fox19}}</ref> State of Ohio Attorney General [[Dave Yost]] later clarified that all [[medical abortions]] were still allowed, and that \"doctors remain free to perform surgical abortions necessary for a mother's health or life, and also surgical abortions that cannot be delayed without jeopardizing the patient's abortion rights.\"<ref name=\"Rowland\"/> On April 6, the State's request for an appeal was dismissed by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statenews.org/post/court-refuses-overrule-ruling-stops-ohio-closing-abortion-clinics|title=Court Refuses To Overrule Ruling That Stops Ohio From Closing Abortion Clinics|website=Statehouse News Bureau| first=Jo | last=Ingles|date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Oklahoma==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oklahoma}}\nIn March, Governor [[Kevin Stitt]] signed an executive order to limit elective medical procedures, later confirming that all types of abortion services were included, except for those necessary in a medical emergency or to \"prevent serious health risks\" to the pregnant person. On April 6, federal judge [[Charles Barnes Goodwin]] blocked the executive order, ruling that the state acted in an arbitrary, unreasonable, and oppressive way, which posed an undue burden on abortion access in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/06/politics/oklahoma-abortion-block-coronavirus/index.html| title=Oklahoma judge blocks state order restricting abortion during coronavirus outbreak| first=Caroline| last=Kelly| date=6 April 2020| access-date=7 April 2020| website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n==Texas==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas}}\nIn Texas, Governor [[Greg Abbott]] issued an executive order on March 22, 2020 that temporarily banned elective medical procedures. Attorney General [[Ken Paxton]] warned on March 23 that all abortions were now prohibited, except those necessary to \"preserve the life or health\" of the pregnant person.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> Those found in violation of the ban could be fined up to $1,000, jailed for 180 days, and have their medical license revoked.<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref name=\"Chung\"/> U.S. District Judge [[Lee Yeakel]] ruled in favor of the clinics on March 26, saying that the temporary ban on abortions \"prevents Texas women from exercising what the Supreme Court has declared is their fundamental constitutional right to terminate a pregnancy before a fetus is viable\".<ref name=\"Chung\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-abortion/u-s-judge-stops-texas-from-curbing-abortions-during-coronavirus-crisis-idUSKBN21H3B1| title=U.S. judges stop Texas, Ohio, Alabama from curbing abortions during coronavirus crisis| first=Andrew| last=Chung| date=30 March 2020| website=Reuters| access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> This ruling was overturned on March 31, 2020, when the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] allowed Texas to reinstate the ban.<ref name=\"Stern\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/fifth-circuit-texas-coronavirus-abortion-ban.html| title=Federal Appeals Court Lets Texas Resume Abortion Ban| first=Mark Joseph| last= Stern| date=31 March 2020| access-date=7 April 2020 | website=Slate}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:Abortion in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Consequences of events]]\n", "name_user": "Anomalocaris", "label": "safe", "comment": "straight apostrophes; improve <ref>s; omit year to keep paragraphs in parallel structure; mdy dates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_abortion_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Alioune Dram\u00e9", "text_new": "'''Alioune Dram\u00e9''' (born c. 1921<ref name=HDoG/> &ndash; died 1 March 1977) was a [[Guinea]]n economist and politician. He also served as an ambassador to [[Ivory Coast]].<ref name=HDoG>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIiHwg3Y5u4C&pg=PA96\n |page=96\n |title=Historical dictionary of Guinea\n |author=Thomas O'Toole, Janice E. Baker\n |publisher=Scarecrow Press\n |year=2005\n |ISBN=0-8108-4634-9}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDram\u00e9 served in the first council of the [[Politburo of the First Republic of Guinea]] as Minister of Finance from 1957.<ref name=Camara2005>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D_MTkPws6lcC&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53\n |page=53ff\n |title=Le redressement national en R\u00e9publique de Guin\u00e9e: les effets pervers\n |author=Djibril Kassomba Camara\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2005\n |ISBN=2-7475-9735-0}}</ref>\nIn this role, he signed the first bank notes of the republic,<ref>{{cite book\n |page=212\n |title=Camp Boiro\n |author=Ardo Ousmane B\u00e2\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=1986\n |ISBN=2-85802-649-1}}</ref> and established the Guinean franc in 1960.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Camara|first1=Mohamed Saliou|last2=O'Toole|first2=Thomas|last3=Baker|first3=Janice|title=Historical Dictionary of Guinea|isbn=9780810878235|page=126|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfcKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA126|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref>\nDrame was made responsible for the plans for economic development of Guinea for the periods 1960-1963, 1964\u20131971 and 1973-1979.<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QJYKPadAjG4C&pg=PA398\n |page=398\n |title=Les ethnies ont une histoire\n |author=Jean-Pierre Chr\u00e9tien, G\u00e9rard Prunier\n |publisher=KARTHALA Editions\n |year=2003\n |ISBN=2-84586-389-6}}</ref>\n\n==United States Relations==\nOn April 24, 1975, Dram\u00e9 delivered a letter from the president of Guinea, [[Ahmed S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]], to [[Gerald Ford]] addressing Guinea's food shortage and requesting assistance from the United States.<ref name=\"ford\">{{cite web|title=Guinea, Republic of - President Ahmed Sekou Toure|url=https://www.fordlibrarymuseum.gov/library/document/0351/1555812.pdf|website=fordmuseumlibrary.gov|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> After the 1976 signing of [[PL 480]] by the American government, Dram\u00e9 returned to the United States on April 27, 1976 with a letter from the Guinean president to start the agreement between the Guinean and United States governments. During this agreement, Dram\u00e9 led a team of Guinean representatives to negotiate the Title I and Title II food provided by PL 480.<ref name=\"ford\" />\n\n==Arrest==\nDram\u00e9 was Minister of Planning when he was arrested on the night of 18/19 July 1976 and imprisoned at [[Camp Boiro]].<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e5u4lXchXYQC&pg=PA174\n |page=174\n |title=S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9: un totalitarisme africain\n |author=Maurice Jeanjean\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2004\n |ISBN=2-7475-7657-4}}</ref>\nAt a press conference on 2 August 1976, [[Ahmed S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]] announced the arrest in [[Conakry]] of Dram\u00e9 and several other alleged plotters, including [[Telli Diallo]], [[Alpha Oumar Barry]] and [[Lamine Kouyat\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VBsVUqu-qkcC&pg=PA183\n |page=184\n |title=Parole fut\u00e9e, peuple dup\u00e9: discours & r\u00e9volution chez S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9\n |author=Alpha Ousmane Barry\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2003\n |ISBN=2-7475-3612-2}}</ref>\nOn 15 February 1977, Dram\u00e9 was placed on the \"black diet\" while in Camp Boiro, which meant he was given no food or water until his death.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Camara|first1=Mohamed Saliou|last2=O'Toole|first2=Thomas|last3=Baker|first3=Janice|title=Historical Dictionary of Guinea|isbn=9780810878235|page=121|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfcKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA121|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> \nHe died on 1 March 1977.<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCuhRbDbIbYC&pg=PA94\n |page=94\n |title=La Guin\u00e9e peut-elle \u00eatre chang\u00e9e?\n |author=Als\u00e9ny Ren\u00e9 Gomez\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2010\n |ISBN=2-296-11963-8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dramae, Alioune}}\n[[Category:Guinean economists]]\n[[Category:Guinean politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Guinea to Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Guinea]]\n[[Category:Deaths by starvation]]\n[[Category:1920s births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Guinean people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in Guinean detention]]\n[[Category:20th-century politicians]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alioune Dram\u00e9''' (born c. 1921<ref name=HDoG/> &ndash; died 1 March 1977) was a [[Guinea]]n economist and politician. He also served as an ambassador to [[Ivory Coast]].<ref name=HDoG>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIiHwg3Y5u4C&pg=PA96\n |page=96\n |title=Historical dictionary of Guinea\n |author=Thomas O'Toole, Janice E. Baker\n |publisher=Scarecrow Press\n |year=2005\n |ISBN=0-8108-4634-9}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDram\u00e9 served in the first council of the [[Politburo of the First Republic of Guinea]] as Minister of Finance from 1957.<ref name=Camara2005>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D_MTkPws6lcC&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53\n |page=53ff\n |title=Le redressement national en R\u00e9publique de Guin\u00e9e: les effets pervers\n |author=Djibril Kassomba Camara\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2005\n |ISBN=2-7475-9735-0}}</ref>\nIn this role, he signed the first bank notes of the republic,<ref>{{cite book\n |page=212\n |title=Camp Boiro\n |author=Ardo Ousmane B\u00e2\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=1986\n |ISBN=2-85802-649-1}}</ref> and established the Guinean franc in 1960.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Camara|first1=Mohamed Saliou|last2=O'Toole|first2=Thomas|last3=Baker|first3=Janice|title=Historical Dictionary of Guinea|isbn=9780810878235|page=126|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfcKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA126|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref>\nDrame was made responsible for the plans for economic development of Guinea for the periods 1960-1963, 1964\u20131971 and 1973-1979.<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QJYKPadAjG4C&pg=PA398\n |page=398\n |title=Les ethnies ont une histoire\n |author=Jean-Pierre Chr\u00e9tien, G\u00e9rard Prunier\n |publisher=KARTHALA Editions\n |year=2003\n |ISBN=2-84586-389-6}}</ref>\n\n==United States Relations==\nOn April 24, 1975, Dram\u00e9 delivered a letter from the president of Guinea, [[Ahmed S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]], to [[Gerald Ford]] addressing Guinea's food shortage and requesting assistance from the United States.<ref name=\"ford\">{{cite web|title=Guinea, Republic of - President Ahmed Sekou Toure|url=https://www.fordlibrarymuseum.gov/library/document/0351/1555812.pdf|website=fordmuseumlibrary.gov|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> After the 1976 signing of [[PL 480]] by the American government, Dram\u00e9 returned to the United States on April 27, 1976 with a letter from the Guinean president to start the agreement between the Guinean and United States governments. During this agreement, Dram\u00e9 led a team of Guinean representatives to negotiate the Title I and Title II food provided by PL 480.<ref name=\"ford\" />\n\n==Arrest==\nDram\u00e9 was Minister of Planning when he was arrested on the night of 18/19 July 1976 and imprisoned at [[Camp Boiro]].<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e5u4lXchXYQC&pg=PA174\n |page=174\n |title=S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9: un totalitarisme africain\n |author=Maurice Jeanjean\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2004\n |ISBN=2-7475-7657-4}}</ref>\nAt a press conference on 2 August 1976, [[Ahmed S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]] announced the arrest in [[Conakry]] of Dram\u00e9 and several other alleged plotters, including [[Telli Diallo]], [[Alpha Oumar Barry]] and [[Lamine Kouyat\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VBsVUqu-qkcC&pg=PA183\n |page=184\n |title=Parole fut\u00e9e, peuple dup\u00e9: discours & r\u00e9volution chez S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9\n |author=Alpha Ousmane Barry\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2003\n |ISBN=2-7475-3612-2}}</ref>\nOn 15 February 1977, Dram\u00e9 was placed on the \"black diet\" while in Camp Boiro, which meant he was given no food or water until his death.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Camara|first1=Mohamed Saliou|last2=O'Toole|first2=Thomas|last3=Baker|first3=Janice|title=Historical Dictionary of Guinea|isbn=9780810878235|page=121|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TfcKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA121|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> \nHe died on 1 March 1977.<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCuhRbDbIbYC&pg=PA94\n |page=94\n |title=La Guin\u00e9e peut-elle \u00eatre chang\u00e9e?\n |author=Als\u00e9ny Ren\u00e9 Gomez\n |publisher=Editions L'Harmattan\n |year=2010\n |ISBN=2-296-11963-8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dramae, Alioune}}\n[[Category:Guinean economists]]\n[[Category:Guinean politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Guinea to Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Guinea]]\n[[Category:Deaths by starvation]]\n[[Category:1920s births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Guinean people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in Guinean detention]]\n[[Category:20th-century politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alioune_Dram%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Alina Zotea", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Alina Zotea \n|image          = Alina Zotea deputat.jpg \n|caption        = \n|office       = Member of the [[Parliament of Moldova]] \n|term_start   = 4 September 2015\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1986|12|08|df=yes}}\n|birth_place    = [[Cantemir, Moldova|Cantemir]], [[Moldova]] \n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Liberal Party (Moldova)|Liberal Party]] <small>(2005-)</small>\n|otherparty     = \n|spouse         = Vlad Durnea (m. 2017)<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.timpul.md/articol/foto----video-deputata-alina-zotea-s-a-maritat---a-avut-o-nunta-cu-daruri-i-cantece-patriotice-120812.html \"Deputata Alina Zotea s-a m\u0103ritat\"], ''Timpul'', October 1, 2017</ref>\n|children       = \n|alma_mater     = [[Moldova State University]]\n|profession     = economist, model\n}}\n'''Alina Zotea''' (born 8 December 1986) is a [[Moldova]]n economist, model and politician.\n\nBorn in [[Cantemir, Moldova|Cantemir]], she became a model at age fifteen, and continued her involvement in the activity through her twenties.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://cms4.jurnal.md/ro/import/2011/3/28/zimbru-are-o-noua-fana-alina-zotea-iubeste-galben-verzii-203056/ \"Zimbru are o nou\u0103 fan\u0103; Alina Zotea iube\u015fte 'galben-verzii'\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, jurnal.md, March 28, 2011</ref> She graduated from high school in 2007, and in 2011 obtained a degree from the economics faculty of [[Moldova State University]].<ref name=\"agora\">{{in lang|ro}} [http://agora.md/stiri/11359/alina-zotea-va-ajunge-deputat-in-parlament \"Alina Zotea va ajunge deputat \u00een Parlament\"], agora.md, July 31, 2015</ref>\n\nZotea joined the [[Liberal Party (Moldova)|Liberal Party]] (PL) in 2005,<ref name=\"agora\"/> and became a personal assistant to party leader [[Mihai Ghimpu]] in 2014. In [[2014 Moldovan parliamentary election|that year's election]] for the [[Parliament of Moldova]], she ran on the party's lists, in 19th position.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.noi.md/md/news_id/48733 \"Ghimpu a m\u0103rturisit unde tinde sex simbolul Alina Zotea \u015fi ce va fi \u00een Moldova dac\u0103 Usat\u00eei va veni la putere\"], noi.md, October 8, 2014</ref> During the campaign, some online commentators questioned her fitness for office, citing her provocative modeling photographs.<ref name=\"agora\"/> In August 2015, when five PL members of parliament resigned in order to join the new [[Strele\u021b Cabinet]], one of the vacancies fell to Zotea, who agreed to fill it.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://curentul.md/politica/alina-zotea-a-acceptat-mandatul-de-deputat-in-urmatorii-ani-imi-propun.html \"Alina Zotea a acceptat mandatul de deputat\"], ''Curentul'', August 11, 2015</ref> Her term began early the following month, after validation from the [[Constitutional Court of Moldova|Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.noi.md/md/news_id/68049 \"Mandatele a nou\u0103 parlamentari noi au fost validate\"], noi.md, September 4, 2015</ref>\n\nIn autumn 2017, Zotea married Vlad Durnea;<ref>[http://protv.md/stiri/divertisment/a-fost-nunta-mare-in-capitala-deputata-alina-zotea-s-a-maritat---2028801.html A fost nunta mare in capitala. Deputata Alina Zotea s-a maritat: invitatii au venit cu daruri patriotice, tinerii insuratei au dansat vals, iar mirele a cantat o piesa populara], protv.md, October 1, 2017 {{in lang|ro}}</ref> she gave birth to a child a year later.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [https://unimedia.info/ro/news/d074d1a4fd94d806/deputata-alina-zotea-a-devenit-mamica.html \"Deputata Alina Zotea a devenit m\u0103mic\u0103\"], Unimedia, October 19, 2018</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zotea, Alina}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cantemir District]]\n[[Category:Moldova State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Moldovan economists]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Moldova) MPs]]\n[[Category:Moldovan female MPs]]\n[[Category:Moldovan female models]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Alina Zotea \n|image          = Alina Zotea deputat.jpg \n|caption        = \n|office       = Member of the [[Parliament of Moldova]] \n|term_start   = 4 September 2015\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1986|12|08|df=yes}}\n|birth_place    = [[Cantemir, Moldova|Cantemir]], [[Moldova]] \n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Liberal Party (Moldova)|Liberal Party]] <small>(2005-)</small>\n|otherparty     = \n|spouse         = Vlad Durnea (m. 2017)<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.timpul.md/articol/foto----video-deputata-alina-zotea-s-a-maritat---a-avut-o-nunta-cu-daruri-i-cantece-patriotice-120812.html \"Deputata Alina Zotea s-a m\u0103ritat\"], ''Timpul'', October 1, 2017</ref>\n|children       = \n|alma_mater     = [[Moldova State University]]\n|profession     = economist, model\n}}\n'''Alina Zotea''' (born 8 December 1986) is a [[Moldova]]n economist, model and politician.\n\nBorn in [[Cantemir, Moldova|Cantemir]], she became a model at age fifteen, and continued her involvement in the activity through her twenties.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://cms4.jurnal.md/ro/import/2011/3/28/zimbru-are-o-noua-fana-alina-zotea-iubeste-galben-verzii-203056/ \"Zimbru are o nou\u0103 fan\u0103; Alina Zotea iube\u015fte 'galben-verzii'\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, jurnal.md, March 28, 2011</ref> She graduated from high school in 2007, and in 2011 obtained a degree from the economics faculty of [[Moldova State University]].<ref name=\"agora\">{{in lang|ro}} [http://agora.md/stiri/11359/alina-zotea-va-ajunge-deputat-in-parlament \"Alina Zotea va ajunge deputat \u00een Parlament\"], agora.md, July 31, 2015</ref>\n\nZotea joined the [[Liberal Party (Moldova)|Liberal Party]] (PL) in 2005,<ref name=\"agora\"/> and became a personal assistant to party leader [[Mihai Ghimpu]] in 2014. In [[2014 Moldovan parliamentary election|that year's election]] for the [[Parliament of Moldova]], she ran on the party's lists, in 19th position.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.noi.md/md/news_id/48733 \"Ghimpu a m\u0103rturisit unde tinde sex simbolul Alina Zotea \u015fi ce va fi \u00een Moldova dac\u0103 Usat\u00eei va veni la putere\"], noi.md, October 8, 2014</ref> During the campaign, some online commentators questioned her fitness for office, citing her provocative modeling photographs.<ref name=\"agora\"/> In August 2015, when five PL members of parliament resigned in order to join the new [[Strele\u021b Cabinet]], one of the vacancies fell to Zotea, who agreed to fill it.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://curentul.md/politica/alina-zotea-a-acceptat-mandatul-de-deputat-in-urmatorii-ani-imi-propun.html \"Alina Zotea a acceptat mandatul de deputat\"], ''Curentul'', August 11, 2015</ref> Her term began early the following month, after validation from the [[Constitutional Court of Moldova|Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.noi.md/md/news_id/68049 \"Mandatele a nou\u0103 parlamentari noi au fost validate\"], noi.md, September 4, 2015</ref>\n\nIn autumn 2017, Zotea married Vlad Durnea;<ref>[http://protv.md/stiri/divertisment/a-fost-nunta-mare-in-capitala-deputata-alina-zotea-s-a-maritat---2028801.html A fost nunta mare in capitala. Deputata Alina Zotea s-a maritat: invitatii au venit cu daruri patriotice, tinerii insuratei au dansat vals, iar mirele a cantat o piesa populara], protv.md, October 1, 2017 {{in lang|ro}}</ref> she gave birth to a child a year later.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [https://unimedia.info/ro/news/d074d1a4fd94d806/deputata-alina-zotea-a-devenit-mamica.html \"Deputata Alina Zotea a devenit m\u0103mic\u0103\"], Unimedia, October 19, 2018</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zotea, Alina}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cantemir District]]\n[[Category:Moldova State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Moldovan economists]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Moldova) MPs]]\n[[Category:Moldovan female MPs]]\n[[Category:Moldovan female models]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alina_Zotea"}
{"title_page": "WISN-TV", "text_new": "{{short description|ABC affiliate in Milwaukee}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WISN-TV\n| city                     = \n| station_logo             = WISN 2012 Logo.png\n| station_branding         = WISN 12 ''(general)''<br>''WISN 12 News'' ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = ''Leading the Way with Important Local Coverage'' ''(news)''<br>''WISN 12: One of America's Leading ABC Stations'' ''(general)''\n| digital                  = 28 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 12 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''12.1:''' [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (since 1977; also 1954\u20131961)<br>'''12.2:''' [[Justice Network]]\n| owner                    = [[Hearst Television]]\n| licensee                 = WISN Hearst Television Inc.\n| location                 = [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1954|10|27|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = ''The '''WIS'''consin '''N'''ews''<br>(former Milwaukee newspaper owned by Hearst, that merged with ''[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]]'')\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = WTVW (1954\u20131955)\n| former_channel_numbers   = {{ubl|'''Analog:'''|12 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]], 1954\u20132009)|'''Digital:'''|34 (UHF, 2005\u20132019)}}\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Primary:'''|[[CBS]] (1961\u20131977)|'''Secondary:'''|[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (1954\u20131955)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 1,000 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|304.7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 65680\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|43|6|42|N|87|55|42|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=inline, title}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://www.wisn.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''WISN-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 12 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital channel]] 28), is an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], United States. Owned by the [[Hearst Television]] subsidiary of [[Hearst Communications]], it is the second-oldest television station to remain with the company in all of its various iterations behind [[WBAL-TV]] in [[Baltimore]]. WISN's studios are located on North 19th Street on the west end of the [[Marquette University]] campus, and its transmitter is located at [[Parks of Milwaukee|Lincoln Park]] in the northeastern part of Milwaukee (next to the [[Weigel Broadcasting]] tower, which is used by [[CBS]] affiliate [[WDJT-TV]], channel 58, and its [[sister station]]s).\n\n==History==\n===First tenure with ABC===\nThe station first signed on the air on October 27, 1954 as '''WTVW''' (for its on-air slogan \"<u>W</u>isconsin's <u>T</u>ele<u>V</u>ision <u>W</u>indow\"). WTVW's transmitter building was built under a tent, as rain had threatened to delay construction. After the building was finished, a second tent was erected, and used for live automobile commercials, until it collapsed one day in early 1955. In early 1955, the station was purchased by the Hearst Corporation, publishers of ''The Milwaukee Sentinel'' and owners of [[WISN (AM)|WISN radio]] (1130 AM); the new owners changed channel 12's call letters to '''WISN-TV''', after its radio sister (whose calls were derived from now-defunct newspaper ''The Wisconsin News'', which merged with the ''Sentinel'' 15 years prior to its sign-on;<ref>\"Hearst acquires WTVW (TV) Milwaukee; [[NBC]] buys [[WVIT|WKNB-TV]] New Britain, Conn.\" ''[[Broadcasting and Cable|Broadcasting - Telecasting]]'', January 10, 1955, pg. 7. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-01-10-BC-0007.pdf]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> the [[WTVW]] calls are now used by the [[The CW|CW]]-affiliated station in [[Evansville, Indiana]]). The station originally operated as a primary ABC affiliate with a secondary [[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] affiliation.<ref name=\"Golem2\"/> WISN-TV lost the DuMont affiliation when that network ceased operations in 1956, leaving it exclusively with ABC.\n\nIn January 1958, WISN-TV became the flagship station of the [[Badger Television Network]], a [[state network|three-station network]] serving Wisconsin that also included [[WFRV-TV]] in [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]] and [[WKOW-TV]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]].<ref name=\"Golem2\">{{cite book| last = Golembiewski| first = Dick | authorlink = | title = Milwaukee Television History: The Analog Years| publisher = Marquette University Press| year = 2008| location = | pages = 213\u2013270| url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-87462-055-4}}</ref> Programs broadcast by the network included ''Homemaker's Holiday'', a [[quiz show]] hosted by Charlie Hanson; ''Good Housekeeping'', hosted by Trudy Beilfuss titled after the [[Good Housekeeping|Hearst magazine of the same name]]; and ''Pretzel Party'', a [[variety show|variety program]] originally hosted by Larry Clark. All three programs originated from WISN-TV's studios. During March 1958, the network also aired Senate Investigation Committee hearings during late-night hours. The network ceased operations on August 8, 1958.<ref name=\"Golem2\"/> WISN-TV and WISN radio would gain an FM radio sister when Hearst signed on WISN-FM (97.3, now [[WRNW]]) in 1961.\n\n===Switch to CBS===\nIn 1961, CBS decided to affiliate with WISN-TV, as its sister radio station had been a longtime affiliate of the [[CBS News Radio|CBS Radio Network]]. As a result, [[Storer Broadcasting]]-owned [[WITI (TV)|WITI-TV]] (channel 6) and WISN swapped networks: channel 12 switched its affiliation to CBS and channel 6 became an ABC affiliate on April 2, 1961.<ref>\"Milwaukee stations to switch networks.\" ''Broadcasting'', January 30, 1961, pg. 9. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-01-30-BC-0009.pdf]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The final ABC network program to air on WISN before it joined CBS was an edition of the ''[[Fight of the Week]]'' with boxers [[Benny Paret]] and [[Emile Griffith]]; it ran the evening before the switch at 9:00&nbsp;p.m. Central Time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Today's Television Picture |work=[[The Milwaukee Journal]] |date=April 1, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2DoaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3yYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7183%2C39539 }}</ref>\n\nDuring channel 12's time with CBS, it served as the default home station for the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[Green Bay Packers]] for the Milwaukee market, and airing [[Super Bowl I|the team's first two]] [[Super Bowl II|Super Bowl appearances]] (also the first two Super Bowl games in NFL history); it was succeeded and preceded in this stead by WITI.\n\nHearst sold the ''Milwaukee Sentinel'' to Journal Publishing (the publishers of the ''Milwaukee Journal'') in 1962, retaining WISN-TV and WISN radio. The ''Journal'' also competed with the ''Sentinel'' (both of which were eventually consolidated into the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' in 1995) in broadcasting as owners of [[WTMJ (AM)|WTMJ radio]] (620 AM) and [[WTMJ-TV]] (channel 4), which Journal operated until April 1, 2015, when Journal and [[E. W. Scripps Company]] merged and split their assets into the broadcast-specific Scripps company, and publishing operations into the short-lived [[Journal Media Group]], which merged only a year later into [[Gannett]].\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | align = right\n | width = 160\n | image1 = WISN-TV-Logo-Straight.jpg\n | caption1 = WISN-TV's main logo since the switch to ABC was announced in 1976, used solely for news imaging from 2006 to 2012. It returned into use as the main logo on all programming on September 17, 2012, paired with the WISN calls to the left in Hearst's trademark [[Bank Gothic]] font, which has been used by the station since 1994 for various elements. The ABC circle logo is added to the station-generated bug for syndicated programming.\n | image2 = Wisn.png\n | caption2 = WISN's 'contemporary 12' logo, used from 2006 as the station ID at the start of its newscasts, entertainment programming, and as the logo bug used during ABC network programs. Slowly fading from use after the station's September 2012 re-imaging.\n}}\n\n===Second tenure with ABC===\nOn September 26, 1976, CBS announced it was moving its Milwaukee affiliation back to WITI-TV.<ref>\"In Brief.\" ''Broadcasting'', September 27, 1976, pg. 28. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/76-OCR/1976-09-27-BC-0028.pdf]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (the text incorrectly states that WISN-TV had been a CBS affiliate since 1954, omitting the 1961 affiliation switch.)</ref> Storer Broadcasting had much better relations with CBS than it reportedly had with ABC; weeks earlier, ABC opted to drop Storer's [[San Diego]] station [[KNSD|KCST-TV]] from the network after a four-year dispute stemming from KCST's successful battle to strip that market's ABC affiliation from [[XETV-TDT|XETV-TV]] in nearby [[Tijuana]], Mexico. Meanwhile, ABC had become the top-rated television network in the United States, thanks in large part to two Milwaukee-set sitcoms: ''[[Happy Days]]'' and ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''. WISN-TV and ABC agreed to a new affiliation contract about a month later;<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/76-OCR/1976-10-18-BC-0036.pdf \"Milwaukee connection.\" ''Broadcasting'', October 18, 1976, pg. 36]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> the two stations swapped networks once again on March 27, 1977; the final CBS program to air on channel 12 was an episode of ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'' with guest [[Ken Berry]], which aired at 9:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]] on the night before the station rejoined ABC (the station also aired the [[United Cerebral Palsy]] Telethon ahead of its return to ABC at 6:00&nbsp;p.m. that Sunday evening).<ref>{{cite news |title=TV Today |work=[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]] |date=March 26, 1977 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HnpQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3BEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6915%2C5652494 }}</ref> WISN even used ''Happy Days'' star [[Henry Winkler]] (in character as [[Fonzie|Arthur \"Fonzie\" Fonzarelli]]) to herald its return to ABC with the slogan \"Happy Days are Here Again\" in on-air and print campaigns leading up to the switch. To this day, WISN-TV has been one of ABC's most successful affiliates, and bills itself as such in its own promotions.\n\nAround the same time, the station was the first which utilized newscast composer [[Frank Gari]]'s \"Hello News\" package, which included an imaging song individualized to each market's city; in this case \"Hello Milwaukee\", which remains well-remembered and remains used in various ways by WISN-TV to the present day, and was cited as one of the factors in driving viewers to the station in the late 1970s and allowing it to be competitive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/250975431.html|title=Hello again, Milwaukee: The little TV jingle that will not die|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=March 21, 2014|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor most of its years with ABC, the station did not include the network's logo next to theirs, branding solely with the channel number and/or call letters vocally and visually (outside of network-created radio promos which listed the station as \"12 ABC\") until 2012, when the network began to contractually require the ABC logo be included with any affiliate's logo redesign. In November 2014, the station unveiled their current logo with the call letters beneath the long-used \"12\" logo form and the ABC logo on the right side of the \"12\" number mark, the first with the ABC logo blended in for all uses, including for news and entertainment programming, and ending a long run where the station's call letters were rendered in [[Bank Gothic]] font. Vocally, the station remains \"WISN 12\". The station is among the few in the nation which has their logo in a [[Digital on-screen graphic|transparent bug]] at all times, including ABC network and news programming, though not during commercial breaks or [[infomercial|paid programming]].\n\nChannel 12 was the first commercial station in the market to produce a [[high-definition television|high-definition]] broadcast, airing the [[Summerfest]] \"Big Bang\" [[fireworks]] show in HD on June 29, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.themilwaukeechannel.com/aboutwisn12/9369238/detail.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 16, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120170141/http://www.themilwaukeechannel.com/aboutwisn12/9369238/detail.html |archive-date=November 20, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Milwaukee PBS|Milwaukee Public Television]] assisted WISN-TV in the production of the broadcast, and have continued to do so each year since, with additional help from sister stations in [[KCRA-TV|Sacramento]] and [[WCVB-TV|Boston]] in later years.\n\nHearst sold WISN radio and what by then became WLTQ to [[iHeartMedia|Clear Channel Communications]] in 1997, and the third floor WLTQ/WISN radio studios were vacated in 2000 after their move to the expanded [[WOKY]] facility in [[Greenfield, Wisconsin|Greenfield]]. All ties between WISN-TV and its former sister radio stations were severed when a longtime agreement with channel 12 to provide forecasts for WISN (AM) and the then-WQBW (now WRNW) and four others within Clear Channel's Milwaukee radio cluster ended on July 27, 2009 (though WRNW continues to transmit from WISN-TV's tower), as WITI began its own weather/news content agreement with the stations.<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/51627887.html Accord puts Channel 6 weather, news on Clear Channel radio stations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727000144/http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/51627887.html |date=July 27, 2009 }}, ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', July 24, 2009.</ref> WISN-TV then began a news content agreement with Saga Communications for its five area radio stations ([[WKLH]], [[WHQG]], [[WJMR-FM]], [[WJYI]] and [[WNRG-FM]]).<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/52029337.html Foxx tells 'Idol' contestants 'the real deal'], ''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel'', July 29, 2009.</ref> Due to the now separate ownership of the two stations, WISN-TV's news staff disclaim both on-air and through their [[social networking]] channels that the station has no connections with WISN radio's [[conservative talk]] format other than sharing the same call letters, a point of contention and confusion during events such as [[live shot]]s at the [[Wisconsin State Capitol]] for the [[2011 Wisconsin protests|2011 state budget debate]].<ref>[http://www.mediabistro.com/tvspy/veteran-wisn-reporter-nick-bohr-heckled-by-protestors-in-madison_b6922 Veteran WISN Reporter Nick Bohr Heckled by Protestors in Madison], ''[[MediaBistro.com|TVSpy]]'', February 22, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, the station added an [[second audio program|SAP audio channel]], allowing the station to carry ABC programming featuring [[audio description]] or a [[Spanish language in the United States|Spanish-language]] [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dub]], and complying with the FCC's requirements to offer audio description.\n\n===Summer 2012 Time Warner Cable carriage dispute===\nAs Hearst and [[Time Warner Cable]] entered into a [[retransmission consent]] dispute that resulted in Hearst's stations being removed from TWC's systems in certain markets on July 10, 2012, WISN was not immediately removed from its Milwaukee area systems in an eleventh hour announcement, as the direct fiber connection between WISN and TWC is also provided by the cable provider to [[Charter Communications]] (which serves outer portions of the market such as western [[Waukesha County, Wisconsin|Waukesha County]] and most of [[Washington County, Wisconsin|Washington]], [[Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin|Fond du Lac]] and [[Sheboygan County, Wisconsin|Sheboygan Counties]]) under a [[Side letter (contract law)|side agreement]] between the providers which TWC and Hearst were contractually obligated to honor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/blog/2012/07/channel-12-stays-on-time-warner---for.html|title=Channel 12 stays on Time Warner Cable \u2013 for now|last=Kirchen|first=Rich|date=July 10, 2012|publisher=[[American City Business Journals|The (Greater Milwaukee) Business Journal]]|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> It was the only Hearst station to remain on TWC during the dispute, but with both Start Over [[video on demand]] and the ability to record station programming to TWC [[digital video recorder|DVR]]s completely removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/battles-between-cable-systems-broadcasters-alienating-viewers-fd62tco-162000155.html|title=Battles between cable systems, broadcasters alienating viewers|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=July 10, 2012|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> Charter then tried to pursue a different method of transmitting WISN's signal to remove itself as an intermediary from the dispute,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/162092455.html#!page=0&pageSize=10&sort=newestfirst|title=WISN-TV disputes Time Warner's 'blackout' assertions|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=July 11, 2012|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> and was able to make the arrangements by July 12,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/162270435.html#!page=1&pageSize=10&sort=newestfirst|title=WISN-TV off Time Warner Cable midnight Thursday|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=July 12, 2012|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> allowing WISN's removal from Time Warner Cable one day later, with WISN's SD and HD channel slots replaced with [[Hallmark Movie Channel]]. The dispute was resolved on July 19, returning the station to TWC's systems that evening.\n\n==Digital television==\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WISN#station|title=RabbitEars.Info|website=www.rabbitears.info|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 12.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=\"2\"| [[16:9]] || WISN-TV || Main WISN-TV programming / [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] \n|-\n| 12.2 || [[480i]] || WISN-SD || [[Justice Network]]\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nWISN-TV shut down its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 12, at 8:30&nbsp;a.m. on June 12, 2009 (the transition was led by a retrospective on the station's history narrated by former longtime anchor Jerry Taff, followed by a still of digital transition information that remained until noon, when its analog transmitter was permanently shut down). The station's digital signal continued to broadcast on its pre-transition [[UHF]] channel 34.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=March 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=August 29, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"FCC Form 387\">[http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101230927&formid=387&fac_num=65680 CDBS Print<! \u2013 Bot generated title \u2013 >]</ref> Through the use of [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]], digital television receivers display the station's [[virtual channel]] as its former VHF analog channel 12. The channel 12 frequency was subsequently used as the post-transition digital signal of [[WBBM-TV]] in [[Chicago]].\n\nOn May 17, 2010, WISN-TV filed an application to upgrade its digital transmitter's power to 1 megawatt, mainly to place the station's digital antenna at the taller height of the dormant analog antenna, which would be replaced by a new digital unit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1360443&Service=DT&Form_id=301&Facility_id=65680|title=Application View ... Redirecting|first=FCC Internet Services|last=Staff|website=licensing.fcc.gov|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> The analog antenna was removed in September 2010, and the digital antenna was activated from the new placement in early October 2010.\n\n==News operation==\nWISN-TV presently broadcasts 34 hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with five hours each weekday and 4\u00bd hours each on Saturdays and Sundays); WISN is one of the few Hearst-owned stations that carries an hour-long midday newscast. The station utilizes two [[Doppler weather radar|weather radars]] as part of its \"Doppler 12 Radar Network\", using radar sites based at the [[National Weather Service]] forecast office in [[Sullivan, Wisconsin|Sullivan]], and atop [[Froedtert Hospital|Froedtert]]'s Community Memorial Hospital in [[Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin|Menomonee Falls]], which is operated by the station.\n\nLongtime anchor Jerry Taff retired in May 2005, as WISN's newscasts began to climb in the ratings. Its success stems from hiring popular local anchors and reporters released from other stations, a stronger ABC schedule, and a period of change at rival WTMJ-TV due to NBC's weaker ratings and changes in its newsroom staff. The station's biggest hire came when longtime WTMJ anchor Mike Gousha joined channel 12 in 2007, a year after he retired as WTMJ's evening news anchor in order to focus on his new position as a distinguished fellow in law and public policy at Marquette University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.marquette.edu/cgi-bin/site.pl?10905&userID=4126|title=Michael R. Gousha - Distinguished Fellow in Law and Public Policy|accessdate=March 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091102184412/http://law.marquette.edu/cgi-bin/site.pl?10905&userID=4126|archive-date=November 2, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gousha served as a political analyst for WISN, and hosted the Sunday morning program ''UpFront with Mike Gousha'', which is a mix of the interview segments familiar to viewers of his former WTMJ program ''Sunday Night'', and local political analysis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisn.com/upfront/index.html|title=UpFront with Mike Gousha|accessdate=March 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401075913/http://www.wisn.com/upfront/index.html|archive-date=April 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hearst syndicated the show to other stations statewide, and in August 2010 all of the stations involved (along with Milwaukee Public Television, which provided technical assistance with HD production) broadcast a Gousha-moderated forum for the Wisconsin [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Governor of Wisconsin|gubernatorial]] candidates called the ''UpFront Town Hall Challenge'' from Marquette's new law building, which was purposefully structured to avoid classification as a traditional debate where either candidate could use the format to \"sell\" themselves. The format was repeated in October 2010 between the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and Republican nominees for governor and [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]].\n\nWISN has gradually expanded its newscast schedule since 2007, and is unusual in programming hour-long newscasts, starting that year with a Sunday at 10 p.m. broadcast and for a time, an hour-long Saturday 6 p.m. newscast (the 6:30&nbsp;p.m. half-hour currently features either ''[[On the Money (2013 TV series)|On the Money]]'' or ''12 Sports Saturday''). On July 30, 2010, WISN, like most of its ABC-affiliated sister stations under Hearst did on that date, added a one-hour extension of its weekend morning newscast from 8 to 9&nbsp;a.m. On September 6, 2010, WISN expanded its weekday morning newscast a half-hour early to 4:30&nbsp;a.m., extending the program to {{frac|2|1|2}} hours.<ref>http://www.tvnewscheck.com/link/2010/08/31/44873/wisn-expands-am-newscast-to-430{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2009, the station began using full-time pillarboxing with the station logo and callsign on the respective sides of the screen for newscasts and other standard-definition programming.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.milwaukeehdtv.org/forums/showpost.php?p=51744&postcount=5 |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720090850/http://www.milwaukeehdtv.org/forums/showpost.php?p=51744&postcount=5 |archive-date=July 20, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Afterwards, the station began to slowly implement [[16:9]] graphical elements; in March 2010, WISN-TV unveiled 16:9-optimized weather alert graphics to allow programs to continue to be shown in HD rather than force a downscale to a modified [[4:3]] mode in which the program was displayed in 3:3 (to much viewer complaint over the years, especially with ABC prime time programming), with the weather warnings taking up the remainder of the screen. [[News ticker]]s and logo bugs were also later upgraded; the only HD news segments until late June 2011 aired on its newscasts the day of the Summerfest \"Big Bang\" fireworks show, usually scenic and human interest pieces, along with Milwaukee Public Television co-productions. On October 10, 2010, the station began broadcasting its newscasts in 16:9 [[widescreen]] [[standard definition television|standard definition]], with the pillarboxes being removed. Then on June 28, 2011, WISN-TV became the third station in Milwaukee (behind WTMJ-TV and WITI) to begin broadcasting its newscasts in high definition. Footage shot in-studio is broadcast in HD, while all news video from on-remote locations was initially upconverted to widescreen standard definition for broadcast. Since 2012, the station has upgraded its mobile units and field cameras to HD as equipment has needed replacement. In May 2013, the station unveiled its first HD skycam, overlooking the downtown [[Cathedral Square Park]].\n\nOn January 24, 2011, WISN-TV expanded its 10 p.m. newscast to one hour (becoming the third Hearst-owned station with an hour-long late local newscast, along with [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]]'s [[KOAT]] and [[Honolulu]]'s [[KITV]]).<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/111873334.html/ WISN-TV expands 10 p.m. news to one hour], ''[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]'', December 14, 2010. Retrieved December 15, 2010.</ref> This bumped ''Access Hollywood'' from its longtime 10:30&nbsp;p.m. slot to 12:30&nbsp;a.m., resulting in [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]] asking for an opt-out from the program's syndication contract with WISN to move ''Access'', ending up on WTMJ at 6:30&nbsp;p.m. on April 11, 2011<ref>[http://www.onmilwaukee.com/movies/articles/tvmoves.html OnMedia: Channel 4 drops its 6:30 news], [[OnMilwaukee.com]], March 24, 2011.</ref> (''Access'' aired at 1:37&nbsp;a.m. from January 2013 until September 2014 due to WTMJ's January 2013 relaunch of its 6:30&nbsp;p.m. newscast as the newsmagazine ''Wisconsin Tonight''; it now airs on WITI in late night at 4:00&nbsp;a.m.).\n\nOn September 10, 2018, the station added an hour-long 11 a.m. local newscast leading into ''GMA Day'' (now ''[[Strahan, Sara and Keke]]''), which coincided with the station introducing a next-generation news set, replacing one utilized since October 2001 with multiple re-facings and equipment replacements in the interim.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/entertainment/television-radio/2018/08/09/wisn-tv-channel-12-adding-hour-long-newscast-11-m/945287002/|title=WISN-TV (Channel 12) is adding an hourlong 11 a.m. newscast|last=Foran|first=Chris|date=August 9, 2018|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref> On January 14, 2019, the station reduced its 10 p.m. newscast to the standard 35 minutes (likely due to its current ABC affiliation agreement), allowing WISN-TV to carry the ABC late night lineup \"live\" and in pattern for the first time in the station's history. The station began to air a nightly half-hour 9 p.m. newscast on WISN-DT2 on April 1, 2019 entitled ''WISN 12 News at 9 on Justice'', joining WITI and WMLW-TV (via WDJT) in carrying news at that time. It joined with many of its fellow Hearst stations in programming a prime time newscast on their .2 subchannels, which are usually associated with MeTV.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/entertainment/television-radio/2019/01/10/wisn-tv-trimming-its-10-p-m-newscast-adding-9-p-m-news-channel-12-2-hearst-justice-milwaukee/2529660002/|title=WISN-TV trimming its 10 p.m. newscast to 35 minutes, adding 9 p.m. news on Channel 12.2|last=Foran|first=Chris|date=January 10, 2019|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> On days where Justice has an hour-long program in the news timeslots, alternate programming like ''Upfront'' and ''Matter of Fact'' is re-aired in the latter half to fill the entire hour. The newscast also features a \"Working for Justice\" segment where a crime or public safety story is highlighted in order to naturally tie into its network's format.\n\n===Notable former on-air staff===\n* [[John Coleman (news weathercaster)|John Coleman]] \u2013 weather anchor (later founded [[The Weather Channel]], deceased)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kusi.com/story/12963605/john-coleman|title=John Coleman bio|publisher=[[KUSI-TV]]|accessdate=March 10, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404154135/http://www.kusi.com/story/12963605/john-coleman|archivedate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Lewis (newsreader)|Dan Lewis]] \u2013 anchor (1982\u20131985; now semi-retired)\n* [[Joel Kleefisch]] \u2013 reporter (1994\u20132003; current [[Wisconsin State Assembly|State Representative]] for Wisconsin's 38th District)\n* [[Rebecca Kleefisch]] \u2013 anchor (1999\u20132004; former [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]])\n* [[DeMarco Morgan]] - anchor/reporter (2004\u20132007; current morning anchor for [[KCBS-TV]] and [[CBS News]] correspondent)\n* [[Shaun Robinson]] \u2013 anchor (later weekend anchor and correspondent of ''Access Hollywood'')\n* [[Jerry Taff]] \u2013 anchor (1979\u20132005; retired)\n* [[Ben Tracy]] \u2013 anchor (now [[Los Angeles]] correspondent for [[CBS News]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/11/broadcasts/main3699611.shtml|title=Ben Tracy biography|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=September 26, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Weyrich]] \u2013 political reporter and weekend anchor; later a prominent conservative activist; deceased<ref>''Fabricated Frenzy'', Paul Weyrich [[Op-Ed]], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', July 13, 2008, p. B3</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{TVQ|WISN-TV}}\n*{{BIA|WISN|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Milwaukee TV}}\n{{ABC Wisconsin}}\n{{Other Wisconsin Stations}}\n{{Hearst-Argyle}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wisn-Tv}}\n[[Category:ABC network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Justice Network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1954]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Milwaukee|ISN-TV]]\n[[Category:Hearst Television]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Former CBS network affiliates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|ABC affiliate in Milwaukee}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WISN-TV\n| city                     = \n| station_logo             = WISN 2012 Logo.png\n| station_branding         = WISN 12 ''(general)''<br>''WISN 12 News'' ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = ''Leading the Way with Important Local Coverage'' ''(news)''<br>''WISN 12: One of America's Leading ABC Stations'' ''(general)''\n| digital                  = 28 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 12 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''12.1:''' [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (since 1977; also 1954\u20131961)<br>'''12.2:''' [[Justice Network]]\n| owner                    = [[Hearst Television]]\n| licensee                 = WISN Hearst Television Inc.\n| location                 = [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1954|10|27|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = ''The '''WIS'''consin '''N'''ews''<br>(former Milwaukee newspaper owned by Hearst, that merged with ''[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]]'')\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = WTVW (1954\u20131955)\n| former_channel_numbers   = {{ubl|'''Analog:'''|12 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]], 1954\u20132009)|'''Digital:'''|34 (UHF, 2005\u20132019)}}\n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Primary:'''|[[CBS]] (1961\u20131977)|'''Secondary:'''|[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (1954\u20131955)}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 1,000 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|304.7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 65680\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|43|6|42|N|87|55|42|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=inline, title}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://www.wisn.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''WISN-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 12 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital channel]] 28), is an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], United States. Owned by the [[Hearst Television]] subsidiary of [[Hearst Communications]], it is the second-oldest television station to remain with the company in all of its various iterations behind [[WBAL-TV]] in [[Baltimore]]. WISN's studios are located on North 19th Street on the west end of the [[Marquette University]] campus, and its transmitter is located at [[Parks of Milwaukee|Lincoln Park]] in the northeastern part of Milwaukee (next to the [[Weigel Broadcasting]] tower, which is used by [[CBS]] affiliate [[WDJT-TV]], channel 58, and its [[sister station]]s).\n\n==History==\n===First tenure with ABC===\nThe station first signed on the air on October 27, 1954 as '''WTVW''' (for its on-air slogan \"<u>W</u>isconsin's <u>T</u>ele<u>V</u>ision <u>W</u>indow\"). WTVW's transmitter building was built under a tent, as rain had threatened to delay construction. After the building was finished, a second tent was erected, and used for live automobile commercials, until it collapsed one day in early 1955. In early 1955, the station was purchased by the Hearst Corporation, publishers of ''The Milwaukee Sentinel'' and owners of [[WISN (AM)|WISN radio]] (1130 AM); the new owners changed channel 12's call letters to '''WISN-TV''', after its radio sister (whose calls were derived from now-defunct newspaper ''The Wisconsin News'', which merged with the ''Sentinel'' 15 years prior to its sign-on;<ref>\"Hearst acquires WTVW (TV) Milwaukee; [[NBC]] buys [[WVIT|WKNB-TV]] New Britain, Conn.\" ''[[Broadcasting and Cable|Broadcasting - Telecasting]]'', January 10, 1955, pg. 7. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/55-OCR/1955-01-10-BC-0007.pdf]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> the [[WTVW]] calls are now used by the [[The CW|CW]]-affiliated station in [[Evansville, Indiana]]). The station originally operated as a primary ABC affiliate with a secondary [[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] affiliation.<ref name=\"Golem2\"/> WISN-TV lost the DuMont affiliation when that network ceased operations in 1956, leaving it exclusively with ABC.\n\nIn January 1958, WISN-TV became the flagship station of the [[Badger Television Network]], a [[state network|three-station network]] serving Wisconsin that also included [[WFRV-TV]] in [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]] and [[WKOW-TV]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]].<ref name=\"Golem2\">{{cite book| last = Golembiewski| first = Dick | authorlink = | title = Milwaukee Television History: The Analog Years| publisher = Marquette University Press| year = 2008| location = | pages = 213\u2013270| url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-87462-055-4}}</ref> Programs broadcast by the network included ''Homemaker's Holiday'', a [[quiz show]] hosted by Charlie Hanson; ''Good Housekeeping'', hosted by Trudy Beilfuss titled after the [[Good Housekeeping|Hearst magazine of the same name]]; and ''Pretzel Party'', a [[variety show|variety program]] originally hosted by Larry Clark. All three programs originated from WISN-TV's studios. During March 1958, the network also aired Senate Investigation Committee hearings during late-night hours. The network ceased operations on August 8, 1958.<ref name=\"Golem2\"/> WISN-TV and WISN radio would gain an FM radio sister when Hearst signed on WISN-FM (97.3, now [[WRNW]]) in 1961.\n\n===Switch to CBS===\nIn 1961, CBS decided to affiliate with WISN-TV, as its sister radio station had been a longtime affiliate of the [[CBS News Radio|CBS Radio Network]]. As a result, [[Storer Broadcasting]]-owned [[WITI (TV)|WITI-TV]] (channel 6) and WISN swapped networks: channel 12 switched its affiliation to CBS and channel 6 became an ABC affiliate on April 2, 1961.<ref>\"Milwaukee stations to switch networks.\" ''Broadcasting'', January 30, 1961, pg. 9. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-01-30-BC-0009.pdf]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The final ABC network program to air on WISN before it joined CBS was an edition of the ''[[Fight of the Week]]'' with boxers [[Benny Paret]] and [[Emile Griffith]]; it ran the evening before the switch at 9:00&nbsp;p.m. Central Time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Today's Television Picture |work=[[The Milwaukee Journal]] |date=April 1, 1961 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2DoaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3yYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7183%2C39539 }}</ref>\n\nDuring channel 12's time with CBS, it served as the default home station for the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[Green Bay Packers]] for the Milwaukee market, and airing [[Super Bowl I|the team's first two]] [[Super Bowl II|Super Bowl appearances]] (also the first two Super Bowl games in NFL history); it was succeeded and preceded in this stead by WITI.\n\nHearst sold the ''Milwaukee Sentinel'' to Journal Publishing (the publishers of the ''Milwaukee Journal'') in 1962, retaining WISN-TV and WISN radio. The ''Journal'' also competed with the ''Sentinel'' (both of which were eventually consolidated into the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' in 1995) in broadcasting as owners of [[WTMJ (AM)|WTMJ radio]] (620 AM) and [[WTMJ-TV]] (channel 4), which Journal operated until April 1, 2015, when Journal and [[E. W. Scripps Company]] merged and split their assets into the broadcast-specific Scripps company, and publishing operations into the short-lived [[Journal Media Group]], which merged only a year later into [[Gannett]].\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | align = right\n | width = 160\n | image1 = WISN-TV-Logo-Straight.jpg\n | caption1 = WISN-TV's main logo since the switch to ABC was announced in 1976, used solely for news imaging from 2006 to 2012. It returned into use as the main logo on all programming on September 17, 2012, paired with the WISN calls to the left in Hearst's trademark [[Bank Gothic]] font, which has been used by the station since 1994 for various elements. The ABC circle logo is added to the station-generated bug for syndicated programming.\n | image2 = Wisn.png\n | caption2 = WISN's 'contemporary 12' logo, used from 2006 as the station ID at the start of its newscasts, entertainment programming, and as the logo bug used during ABC network programs. Slowly fading from use after the station's September 2012 re-imaging.\n}}\n\n===Second tenure with ABC===\nOn September 26, 1976, CBS announced it was moving its Milwaukee affiliation back to WITI-TV.<ref>\"In Brief.\" ''Broadcasting'', September 27, 1976, pg. 28. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/76-OCR/1976-09-27-BC-0028.pdf]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (the text incorrectly states that WISN-TV had been a CBS affiliate since 1954, omitting the 1961 affiliation switch.)</ref> Storer Broadcasting had much better relations with CBS than it reportedly had with ABC; weeks earlier, ABC opted to drop Storer's [[San Diego]] station [[KNSD|KCST-TV]] from the network after a four-year dispute stemming from KCST's successful battle to strip that market's ABC affiliation from [[XETV-TDT|XETV-TV]] in nearby [[Tijuana]], Mexico. Meanwhile, ABC had become the top-rated television network in the United States, thanks in large part to two Milwaukee-set sitcoms: ''[[Happy Days]]'' and ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''. WISN-TV and ABC agreed to a new affiliation contract about a month later;<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/76-OCR/1976-10-18-BC-0036.pdf \"Milwaukee connection.\" ''Broadcasting'', October 18, 1976, pg. 36]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> the two stations swapped networks once again on March 27, 1977; the final CBS program to air on channel 12 was an episode of ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'' with guest [[Ken Berry]], which aired at 9:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]] on the night before the station rejoined ABC (the station also aired the [[United Cerebral Palsy]] Telethon ahead of its return to ABC at 6:00&nbsp;p.m. that Sunday evening).<ref>{{cite news |title=TV Today |work=[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]] |date=March 26, 1977 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HnpQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3BEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6915%2C5652494 }}</ref> WISN even used ''Happy Days'' star [[Henry Winkler]] (in character as [[Fonzie|Arthur \"Fonzie\" Fonzarelli]]) to herald its return to ABC with the slogan \"Happy Days are Here Again\" in on-air and print campaigns leading up to the switch. To this day, WISN-TV has been one of ABC's most successful affiliates, and bills itself as such in its own promotions.\n\nAround the same time, the station was the first which utilized newscast composer [[Frank Gari]]'s \"Hello News\" package, which included an imaging song individualized to each market's city; in this case \"Hello Milwaukee\", which remains well-remembered and remains used in various ways by WISN-TV to the present day, and was cited as one of the factors in driving viewers to the station in the late 1970s and allowing it to be competitive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/250975431.html|title=Hello again, Milwaukee: The little TV jingle that will not die|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=March 21, 2014|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor most of its years with ABC, the station did not include the network's logo next to theirs, branding solely with the channel number and/or call letters vocally and visually (outside of network-created radio promos which listed the station as \"12 ABC\") until 2012, when the network began to contractually require the ABC logo be included with any affiliate's logo redesign. In November 2014, the station unveiled their current logo with the call letters beneath the long-used \"12\" logo form and the ABC logo on the right side of the \"12\" number mark, the first with the ABC logo blended in for all uses, including for news and entertainment programming, and ending a long run where the station's call letters were rendered in [[Bank Gothic]] font. Vocally, the station remains \"WISN 12\". The station is among the few in the nation which has their logo in a [[Digital on-screen graphic|transparent bug]] at all times, including ABC network and news programming, though not during commercial breaks or [[infomercial|paid programming]].\n\nChannel 12 was the first commercial station in the market to produce a [[high-definition television|high-definition]] broadcast, airing the [[Summerfest]] \"Big Bang\" [[fireworks]] show in HD on June 29, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.themilwaukeechannel.com/aboutwisn12/9369238/detail.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 16, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120170141/http://www.themilwaukeechannel.com/aboutwisn12/9369238/detail.html |archive-date=November 20, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Milwaukee PBS|Milwaukee Public Television]] assisted WISN-TV in the production of the broadcast, and have continued to do so each year since, with additional help from sister stations in [[KCRA-TV|Sacramento]] and [[WCVB-TV|Boston]] in later years.\n\nHearst sold WISN radio and what by then became WLTQ to [[iHeartMedia|Clear Channel Communications]] in 1997, and the third floor WLTQ/WISN radio studios were vacated in 2000 after their move to the expanded [[WOKY]] facility in [[Greenfield, Wisconsin|Greenfield]]. All ties between WISN-TV and its former sister radio stations were severed when a longtime agreement with channel 12 to provide forecasts for WISN (AM) and the then-WQBW (now WRNW) and four others within Clear Channel's Milwaukee radio cluster ended on July 27, 2009 (though WRNW continues to transmit from WISN-TV's tower), as WITI began its own weather/news content agreement with the stations.<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/51627887.html Accord puts Channel 6 weather, news on Clear Channel radio stations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727000144/http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/51627887.html |date=July 27, 2009 }}, ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', July 24, 2009.</ref> WISN-TV then began a news content agreement with Saga Communications for its five area radio stations ([[WKLH]], [[WHQG]], [[WJMR-FM]], [[WJYI]] and [[WNRG-FM]]).<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/52029337.html Foxx tells 'Idol' contestants 'the real deal'], ''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel'', July 29, 2009.</ref> Due to the now separate ownership of the two stations, WISN-TV's news staff disclaim both on-air and through their [[social networking]] channels that the station has no connections with WISN radio's [[conservative talk]] format other than sharing the same call letters, a point of contention and confusion during events such as [[live shot]]s at the [[Wisconsin State Capitol]] for the [[2011 Wisconsin protests|2011 state budget debate]].<ref>[http://www.mediabistro.com/tvspy/veteran-wisn-reporter-nick-bohr-heckled-by-protestors-in-madison_b6922 Veteran WISN Reporter Nick Bohr Heckled by Protestors in Madison], ''[[MediaBistro.com|TVSpy]]'', February 22, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, the station added an [[second audio program|SAP audio channel]], allowing the station to carry ABC programming featuring [[audio description]] or a [[Spanish language in the United States|Spanish-language]] [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dub]], and complying with the FCC's requirements to offer audio description.\n\n===Summer 2012 Time Warner Cable carriage dispute===\nAs Hearst and [[Time Warner Cable]] entered into a [[retransmission consent]] dispute that resulted in Hearst's stations being removed from TWC's systems in certain markets on July 10, 2012, WISN was not immediately removed from its Milwaukee area systems in an eleventh hour announcement, as the direct fiber connection between WISN and TWC is also provided by the cable provider to [[Charter Communications]] (which serves outer portions of the market such as western [[Waukesha County, Wisconsin|Waukesha County]] and most of [[Washington County, Wisconsin|Washington]], [[Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin|Fond du Lac]] and [[Sheboygan County, Wisconsin|Sheboygan Counties]]) under a [[Side letter (contract law)|side agreement]] between the providers which TWC and Hearst were contractually obligated to honor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/blog/2012/07/channel-12-stays-on-time-warner---for.html|title=Channel 12 stays on Time Warner Cable \u2013 for now|last=Kirchen|first=Rich|date=July 10, 2012|publisher=[[American City Business Journals|The (Greater Milwaukee) Business Journal]]|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> It was the only Hearst station to remain on TWC during the dispute, but with both Start Over [[video on demand]] and the ability to record station programming to TWC [[digital video recorder|DVR]]s completely removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/tvradio/battles-between-cable-systems-broadcasters-alienating-viewers-fd62tco-162000155.html|title=Battles between cable systems, broadcasters alienating viewers|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=July 10, 2012|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> Charter then tried to pursue a different method of transmitting WISN's signal to remove itself as an intermediary from the dispute,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/162092455.html#!page=0&pageSize=10&sort=newestfirst|title=WISN-TV disputes Time Warner's 'blackout' assertions|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=July 11, 2012|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> and was able to make the arrangements by July 12,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/162270435.html#!page=1&pageSize=10&sort=newestfirst|title=WISN-TV off Time Warner Cable midnight Thursday|last=Dudek|first=Duane|date=July 12, 2012|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> allowing WISN's removal from Time Warner Cable one day later, with WISN's SD and HD channel slots replaced with [[Hallmark Movie Channel]]. The dispute was resolved on July 19, returning the station to TWC's systems that evening.\n\n==Digital television==\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WISN#station|title=RabbitEars.Info|website=www.rabbitears.info|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 12.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=\"2\"| [[16:9]] || WISN-TV || Main WISN-TV programming / [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] \n|-\n| 12.2 || [[480i]] || WISN-SD || [[Justice Network]]\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nWISN-TV shut down its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 12, at 8:30&nbsp;a.m. on June 12, 2009 (the transition was led by a retrospective on the station's history narrated by former longtime anchor Jerry Taff, followed by a still of digital transition information that remained until noon, when its analog transmitter was permanently shut down). The station's digital signal continued to broadcast on its pre-transition [[UHF]] channel 34.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=March 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=August 29, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"FCC Form 387\">[http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101230927&formid=387&fac_num=65680 CDBS Print<! \u2013 Bot generated title \u2013 >]</ref> Through the use of [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]], digital television receivers display the station's [[virtual channel]] as its former VHF analog channel 12. The channel 12 frequency was subsequently used as the post-transition digital signal of [[WBBM-TV]] in [[Chicago]].\n\nOn May 17, 2010, WISN-TV filed an application to upgrade its digital transmitter's power to 1 megawatt, mainly to place the station's digital antenna at the taller height of the dormant analog antenna, which would be replaced by a new digital unit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1360443&Service=DT&Form_id=301&Facility_id=65680|title=Application View ... Redirecting|first=FCC Internet Services|last=Staff|website=licensing.fcc.gov|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> The analog antenna was removed in September 2010, and the digital antenna was activated from the new placement in early October 2010.\n\n==News operation==\nWISN-TV presently broadcasts 34 hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with five hours each weekday and 4\u00bd hours each on Saturdays and Sundays); WISN is one of the few Hearst-owned stations that carries an hour-long midday newscast. The station utilizes two [[Doppler weather radar|weather radars]] as part of its \"Doppler 12 Radar Network\", using radar sites based at the [[National Weather Service]] forecast office in [[Sullivan, Wisconsin|Sullivan]], and atop [[Froedtert Hospital|Froedtert]]'s Community Memorial Hospital in [[Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin|Menomonee Falls]], which is operated by the station.\n\nLongtime anchor Jerry Taff retired in May 2005, as WISN's newscasts began to climb in the ratings. Its success stems from hiring popular local anchors and reporters released from other stations, a stronger ABC schedule, and a period of change at rival WTMJ-TV due to NBC's weaker ratings and changes in its newsroom staff. The station's biggest hire came when longtime WTMJ anchor Mike Gousha joined channel 12 in 2007, a year after he retired as WTMJ's evening news anchor in order to focus on his new position as a distinguished fellow in law and public policy at Marquette University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.marquette.edu/cgi-bin/site.pl?10905&userID=4126|title=Michael R. Gousha - Distinguished Fellow in Law and Public Policy|accessdate=March 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091102184412/http://law.marquette.edu/cgi-bin/site.pl?10905&userID=4126|archive-date=November 2, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gousha served as a political analyst for WISN, and hosted the Sunday morning program ''UpFront with Mike Gousha'', which is a mix of the interview segments familiar to viewers of his former WTMJ program ''Sunday Night'', and local political analysis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisn.com/upfront/index.html|title=UpFront with Mike Gousha|accessdate=March 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401075913/http://www.wisn.com/upfront/index.html|archive-date=April 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hearst syndicated the show to other stations statewide, and in August 2010 all of the stations involved (along with Milwaukee Public Television, which provided technical assistance with HD production) broadcast a Gousha-moderated forum for the Wisconsin [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Governor of Wisconsin|gubernatorial]] candidates called the ''UpFront Town Hall Challenge'' from Marquette's new law building, which was purposefully structured to avoid classification as a traditional debate where either candidate could use the format to \"sell\" themselves. The format was repeated in October 2010 between the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and Republican nominees for governor and [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]].\n\nWISN has gradually expanded its newscast schedule since 2007, and is unusual in programming hour-long newscasts, starting that year with a Sunday at 10 p.m. broadcast and for a time, an hour-long Saturday 6 p.m. newscast (the 6:30&nbsp;p.m. half-hour currently features either ''[[On the Money (2013 TV series)|On the Money]]'' or ''12 Sports Saturday''). On July 30, 2010, WISN, like most of its ABC-affiliated sister stations under Hearst did on that date, added a one-hour extension of its weekend morning newscast from 8 to 9&nbsp;a.m. On September 6, 2010, WISN expanded its weekday morning newscast a half-hour early to 4:30&nbsp;a.m., extending the program to {{frac|2|1|2}} hours.<ref>http://www.tvnewscheck.com/link/2010/08/31/44873/wisn-expands-am-newscast-to-430{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2009, the station began using full-time pillarboxing with the station logo and callsign on the respective sides of the screen for newscasts and other standard definition programming.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.milwaukeehdtv.org/forums/showpost.php?p=51744&postcount=5 |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 22, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720090850/http://www.milwaukeehdtv.org/forums/showpost.php?p=51744&postcount=5 |archive-date=July 20, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Afterwards, the station began to slowly implement [[16:9]] graphical elements; in March 2010, WISN-TV unveiled 16:9-optimized weather alert graphics to allow programs to continue to be shown in HD rather than force a downscale to a modified [[4:3]] mode in which the program was displayed in 3:3 (to much viewer complaint over the years, especially with ABC prime time programming), with the weather warnings taking up the remainder of the screen. [[News ticker]]s and logo bugs were also later upgraded; the only HD news segments until late June 2011 aired on its newscasts the day of the Summerfest \"Big Bang\" fireworks show, usually scenic and human interest pieces, along with Milwaukee Public Television co-productions. On October 10, 2010, the station began broadcasting its newscasts in 16:9 [[widescreen]] [[standard definition television|standard definition]], with the pillarboxes being removed. Then on June 28, 2011, WISN-TV became the third station in Milwaukee (behind WTMJ-TV and WITI) to begin broadcasting its newscasts in high definition. Footage shot in-studio is broadcast in HD, while all news video from on-remote locations was initially upconverted to widescreen standard definition for broadcast. Since 2012, the station has upgraded its mobile units and field cameras to HD as equipment has needed replacement. In May 2013, the station unveiled its first HD skycam, overlooking the downtown [[Cathedral Square Park]].\n\nOn January 24, 2011, WISN-TV expanded its 10 p.m. newscast to one hour (becoming the third Hearst-owned station with an hour-long late local newscast, along with [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]]'s [[KOAT]] and [[Honolulu]]'s [[KITV]]).<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/111873334.html/ WISN-TV expands 10 p.m. news to one hour], ''[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]'', December 14, 2010. Retrieved December 15, 2010.</ref> This bumped ''Access Hollywood'' from its longtime 10:30&nbsp;p.m. slot to 12:30&nbsp;a.m., resulting in [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]] asking for an opt-out from the program's syndication contract with WISN to move ''Access'', ending up on WTMJ at 6:30&nbsp;p.m. on April 11, 2011<ref>[http://www.onmilwaukee.com/movies/articles/tvmoves.html OnMedia: Channel 4 drops its 6:30 news], [[OnMilwaukee.com]], March 24, 2011.</ref> (''Access'' aired at 1:37&nbsp;a.m. from January 2013 until September 2014 due to WTMJ's January 2013 relaunch of its 6:30&nbsp;p.m. newscast as the newsmagazine ''Wisconsin Tonight''; it now airs on WITI in late night at 4:00&nbsp;a.m.).\n\nOn September 10, 2018, the station added an hour-long 11 a.m. local newscast leading into ''GMA Day'' (now ''[[Strahan, Sara and Keke]]''), which coincided with the station introducing a next generation news set, replacing one utilized since October 2001 with multiple re-facings and equipment replacements in the interim.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/entertainment/television-radio/2018/08/09/wisn-tv-channel-12-adding-hour-long-newscast-11-m/945287002/|title=WISN-TV (Channel 12) is adding an hourlong 11 a.m. newscast|last=Foran|first=Chris|date=August 9, 2018|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref> On January 14, 2019, the station reduced its 10 p.m. newscast to the standard 35 minutes (likely due to its current ABC affiliation agreement), allowing WISN-TV to carry the ABC late night lineup \"live\" and in pattern for the first time in the station's history. The station began to air a nightly half-hour 9 p.m. newscast on WISN-DT2 on April 1, 2019 entitled ''WISN 12 News at 9 on Justice'', joining WITI and WMLW-TV (via WDJT) in carrying news at that time. It joined with many of its fellow Hearst stations in programming a prime time newscast on their .2 subchannels, which are usually associated with MeTV.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/entertainment/television-radio/2019/01/10/wisn-tv-trimming-its-10-p-m-newscast-adding-9-p-m-news-channel-12-2-hearst-justice-milwaukee/2529660002/|title=WISN-TV trimming its 10 p.m. newscast to 35 minutes, adding 9 p.m. news on Channel 12.2|last=Foran|first=Chris|date=January 10, 2019|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> On days where Justice has an hour-long program in the news timeslots, alternate programming like ''Upfront'' and ''Matter of Fact'' is re-aired in the latter half to fill the entire hour. The newscast also features a \"Working for Justice\" segment where a crime or public safety story is highlighted in order to naturally tie into its network's format.\n\n===Notable former on-air staff===\n* [[John Coleman (news weathercaster)|John Coleman]] \u2013 weather anchor (later founded [[The Weather Channel]], deceased)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kusi.com/story/12963605/john-coleman|title=John Coleman bio|publisher=[[KUSI-TV]]|accessdate=March 10, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404154135/http://www.kusi.com/story/12963605/john-coleman|archivedate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Lewis (newsreader)|Dan Lewis]] \u2013 anchor (1982\u20131985; now semi-retired)\n* [[Joel Kleefisch]] \u2013 reporter (1994\u20132003; current [[Wisconsin State Assembly|State Representative]] for Wisconsin's 38th District)\n* [[Rebecca Kleefisch]] \u2013 anchor (1999\u20132004; former [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]])\n* [[DeMarco Morgan]] - anchor/reporter (2004\u20132007; current morning anchor for [[KCBS-TV]] and [[CBS News]] correspondent)\n* [[Shaun Robinson]] \u2013 anchor (later weekend anchor and correspondent of ''Access Hollywood'')\n* [[Jerry Taff]] \u2013 anchor (1979\u20132005; retired)\n* [[Ben Tracy]] \u2013 anchor (now [[Los Angeles]] correspondent for [[CBS News]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/11/broadcasts/main3699611.shtml|title=Ben Tracy biography|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=September 26, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Weyrich]] \u2013 political reporter and weekend anchor; later a prominent conservative activist; deceased<ref>''Fabricated Frenzy'', Paul Weyrich [[Op-Ed]], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', July 13, 2008, p. B3</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{TVQ|WISN-TV}}\n*{{BIA|WISN|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Milwaukee TV}}\n{{ABC Wisconsin}}\n{{Other Wisconsin Stations}}\n{{Hearst-Argyle}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wisn-Tv}}\n[[Category:ABC network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Justice Network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1954]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Milwaukee|ISN-TV]]\n[[Category:Hearst Television]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Former CBS network affiliates]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNews operation:Punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WISN-TV"}
{"title_page": "M. Magendran", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Datuk\n| name               = M. Magendran\n| image              = M. Magendran Everest, Nepal 1997.jpg\n| caption            = M. Magendran on the summit of Mount Everest - 23 May 1997\n| native_name        = \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd. \u0bae\u0b95\u0bc7\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba9\u0bcd\n| native_name_lang   = [[Tamil language]]\n| birth_name         = Magendran M. Munisamy\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|6 December 1963}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = * {{Flag|Malaysia}} :  Malaysian\n| education          = M. Ed,<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Malaya Theses and Dissertations|url=http://www.diglib.um.edu.my/umtheses/browse.asp?page=31&level=all&faculty=P&year=all#sthash.F6yYG5vC.dpbs}}</ref> [[University of Malaya]], Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. \nB. Sp. Sc  (Hons), University of Malaya, Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.\n| spouse             = [[Malay title#Datin|Datin]] V. Senthamarai<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/07/11/mt-everest-climbers-happy-to-get-recognition-for-their-feat/|title= On top of the world again - Mt. Everest climbers happy to get recognition for their feat|author=Manjit Kaur|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 August 2019}}</ref> \n| children           = 3\n| occupation         = Teacher / Sports Manager<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/sport/other-sport/2013/04/18/german-stint-for-rayzam-and-hup-wei/|title=German stint for Rayzam and Hup Wei|publisher=The Star|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/sport/athletics/2015/02/27/lee-hup-wei-might-miss-sea-games-again/|title=High jumper Hup Wei might miss SEA Games again |author=Aftar Singh|newspaper=The Star Online|date=27 February 2015|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> \n| known_for          = * First [[Malaysians|Malaysian]]/[[Tamil people|Tamil]] to conquer [[Mount Everest]]\n* The Malaysian title of [[Malay titles#Datuk|Datuk]]\n* Photo on postage stamp<ref name=\"Random\" /><ref name=\"thebrandlaureate.net\">{{cite web|title=Datuk M Magendran - The first Malaysian Mount Everest summiteer|url=http://thebrandlaureate.net/2016/10/25/datuk-m-magendran/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Millenium Series III - Spirit of New Malaysian|url=https://myfdc.me/malaysia-first-day-covers/1991-2000/2000-2/|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Siri Milenium III - Semangat Malaysia Baru|url=http://sampulfdc.blogspot.com/2010/11/siri-milenium-iii-semangat-malaysia.html|accessdate= 6 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}<!-- [[wp:COMMONNAME]] is by far \"M. Magendran\", so that is the correct title of this article.  P. Ellsworth, ed. -->\n[[Malay title#Datuk|Datuk]] '''M. Magendran''' [[Order of Meritorious Service|PJN]] [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|DSPN]] [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia|JSM]] [[Order of the Defender of the Realm#Officer|KMN]] [[List of post-nominal letters (Selangor)|AMS]] ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd. \u0bae\u0b95\u0bc7\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba9\u0bcd) born '''Magendran M. Munisamy'''<ref name=\"Messner\">{{cite book |title=Everest: Expedition to the Ultimate |author=Reinhold Messner |authorlink=Reinhold Messner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E4Tf5tL407EC&pg=PA256&dq=%22Magendran%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LbHqUbb1MIiI9ATQ6YGAAg&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Magendran%22&f=false |publisher=The Mountaineers Books |year=1999 |page=256 |isbn=0-89886-648-0 |accessdate=20 July 2013}}</ref> on\n6 December 1963<ref name=\"thebrandlaureate.net\">{{cite web|title=Datuk M Magendran - The first Malaysian Mount Everest summiteer|url=http://thebrandlaureate.net/2016/10/25/datuk-m-magendran/}}</ref>   in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]) is the first Malaysian [[mountain climber]] and first [[Tamil people|Tamil]] to conquer the summit of [[Mount Everest]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Malaysia's Everest Quest |url=http://www.hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=5023 |date=1 September 1997 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923050944/http://hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=5023 |archivedate=23 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mountaineering |author=Khalid Yunus |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com.my/volume15/138.html |publisher=encyclopedia.com |work=The Encyclopedia of Malaysia |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617233929/http://www.encyclopedia.com.my/volume15/138.html |archivedate=17 June 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Magendran's party ascended the [[South Col]] on the [[Mount Everest#Southeast ridge|southeast ridge]].<ref name=\"Messner\" /> He stepped onto Everest's summit on 23 May 1997, at 11:55&nbsp;a.m. local time. He was followed by N. Mohanadas (Mohanadas Nagappan), who reached the summit a few minutes later at 12:10&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Best Records of the Year |url=http://www.malaysiarecords.com.my/recordoftheyear.php |author=The Malaysia Book of Records |authorlink=Malaysian Book of Records |publisher=Malaysiarecords.com.my |year=1995\u20132012 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020100436/http://www.malaysiarecords.com.my/recordoftheyear.php |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mount Everest Expedition |author=Sambutan Kemerdekaan |url=http://www.malaysiamerdeka.gov.my/v2/en/achievements/271-pendakian-gunung-everest |publisher=Malaysiamerdeka.gov.my |year=1997 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518080052/http://www.malaysiamerdeka.gov.my/v2/en/achievements/271-pendakian-gunung-everest |archivedate=18 May 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two [[mountaineer]]s were part of the first \"Malaysia-Everest Project 97\" jointly organised by the Malaysia Mountaineering Association and the [[Ministry of Youth and Sports (Malaysia)|Ministry of Youth and Sports of Malaysia]].  Also with their team of ten people was [[M. Moorthy]] (Moorthy Maniam), a Malaysian of [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] descent.\n\nMount Everest is the world's highest mountain, with a peak at 8,848 metres (29,029&nbsp;ft) above sea level. Its summit was first achieved in 1953 after numerous failed attempts that began in 1921. The first person to finally set foot on its summit was [[New Zealand]]er Sir [[Edmund Hillary]], who was accompanied by [[Tenzing Norgay]] of [[India]].  Both M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas were conferred [[Malay titles#Datuk|Datukships]] by the [[Penang]] state government in 2010 for their [[Himalaya]]n achievement.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mt Everest climbers get Datukships |author=K. Suthakar |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/story.aspx?file=%2f2010%2f7%2f10%2fnation%2f6637881&sec=nation |newspaper=[[The Star Online]] |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020120903/http://www.thestar.com.my/story.aspx?file=%2f2010%2f7%2f10%2fnation%2f6637881&sec=nation |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two ethnic Indians receive Malaysia's Datukship title |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/two-ethnic-indians-receive-malaysias-datukship-title/645271/ |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=12 July 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref> Both men were also conferred the Federal 'Datukships' title by the King of Malaysia in Jun 2011 [http://www.thestar.com.my/story.aspx/?file=%2F2011%2F6%2F5%2Fnation%2F8842050&sec=nation]\n\nIn June 2013, Datuk Magendran, who is considered a pioneer among Malaysians, gave advice for those mountain climbers who would brave the hazards of the world's highest peak:\n{{quote|ALL safety and preparatory efforts must be taken before setting out on a mountain climb, especially when it involves the world's tallest mountain.  One should be ''very well prepared'' and must have undergone rigorous physical and mental training before taking on the mammoth peak, [...] One must undergo sufficient training and preparation, which includes endurance training and altitude training.  I had been involved in outdoor activities such as mountain climbing and jungle-trekking for ten years and received almost three years of rigorous training before our team left for Mount Everest in 1997.<ref name=\"newstraits\">{{Cite news |title=Safety key to Everest ascent |author=Kalbana Perimbanayagam and Hashini Kavishtri Kannan |url=http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/safety-key-to-everest-ascent-1.297890 |publisher=[[New Straits Times Online]] |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=17 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616125658/http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/safety-key-to-everest-ascent-1.297890 |archivedate=16 June 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}\n\nMagendran urged future climbers and trekkers not to overlook their health before and during the climb, adding that any symptom that was overlooked could be fatal.  He also reminded, \"Trekkers should keep an eye on the health of their teammates, too.\"<ref name=\"newstraits\" />\n\nThe year 1997 also commemorated the 40th anniversary of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaysian independence]].<ref name=\"am002\">The UK Statute Law Database: [http://www.statutelaw.gov.uk/content.aspx?LegType=All%20Primary&PageNumber=72&NavFrom=2&parentActiveTextDocId=1118475&ActiveTextDocId=1118475&filesize=15776 Federation of Malaya Independence Act 1957 (c. 60)]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved 19 July 2013</ref> In 2000, both M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas were pictured on their nation's postage stamps.[http://sampulfdc.blogspot.com/2010/11/siri-milenium-iii-semangat-malaysia.html]<ref name=\"Random\">{{Cite book |title=Malaysia at Random |series=At Random Series |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5VvvOi9mRHIC&pg=PA75&dq=%22M.+Magendran%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eaXqUd7gIIrW9ATCkIHADQ&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA |publisher=[[Editions Didier Millet]] |page=75 |year=2010 |isbn=9814217956 |accessdate=20 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nMagendran is a vice-principal in SMK USJ 8, in Subang Jaya. Being a Sports Science and Physical Education graduate, he also teaches Physical Education.<ref name=\"The Star Online 2017\">{{cite web |website=The Star Online |date=4 June 2017| title=Still feeling on top of the world |author=Shahanaaz Habib|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/06/04/still-feeling-on-top-of-the-world-twenty-years-ago-malaysia-made-history-when-m-magendran-and-n-moha/ |access-date=3 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018073830/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/06/04/still-feeling-on-top-of-the-world-twenty-years-ago-malaysia-made-history-when-m-magendran-and-n-moha/ |archivedate=18 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 (Malaysia Can Do It!) ==\n[[File:Malaysian Everest `97 - Official logo.jpg|thumb|The official logo of the first Malaysian Everest Expedition (Malaysia-Everest `97)]]\n\nThe idea of `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 was first mooted in 1993 by [[Nestle]] and made its debut as part of a marketing campaign for [[Milo (drink)]], and a confidence boost for the Malaysian contingent during the 1993 [[Southeast Asia Games]] in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://says.com/my/lifestyle/the-origin-of-the-slogan-malaysia-boleh |title=Did you know:The iconic `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 Slogan originated from a marketing campaign|author=Samantha Khor |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref>\nThe`Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 slogan slowly gained influence as a signature battle cry in the mid 1990s when Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad]] co-opted the catch phrase to spur the nation's [[Wawasan 2020|Vision 2020]]. Likewise, the Malaysia-Everest `97 organizing committee also incorporated the phrase to its official expedition logo to instill a sense of confidence and perseverance among the climbers. And the force of the slogan worked both ways, it gave the climbers the competitive spirit to strive for excellence and the success of the expedition gave the much needed oomph to the `Malaysia Boleh! spirit. The slogan became more popular and inspired many Malaysians to embark on other adventures like the Read brothers who walked to the last degree of the North pole (1998), Dato' [[Azhar Mansor]] who sailed solo around the world (1999), Dato' [[Abdul Malik Mydin]] who swam across the English Channel (2003) and many more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/travel/malaysia/2011/04/06/malaysia-boleh/|title=Malaysia Boleh |author=Maf73 |publisher=The Star |date=6 April 2011|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebrandlaureate.net/2016/10/25/datuk-m-magendran/|title=M. Magendran- The first Malaysian Mount  Everest Summiteer}}</ref>\nThe stories of these exemplary Malaysians never cease to amaze the Prime Minister whenever he speaks about discipline, patience and over-coming challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/08/31/pm-discipline-and-patience-are-also-vital/|title=PM:Discipline and patience are also vital|publisher=The Star|date=31 August 2003|accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref> Tun Dr. [[Mahathir Mohamad]] in his book, A Doctor in the House: The Memoirs of Tun Dr. Mahathir Mohamad (pg. 589) stated that:\n{{quote|The new `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 (Malaysia can do it) seemed to take hold and coincide with the period of growth. [[The Malaysia Book of Records]] had also been started and people now try to pull off unusual feat to get into it. The new competitive spirit, combined with the desire to show that Malaysians could do anything, generated much excitement in the country. Datuk Azhar Mansor sailed solo around the world; Datuk M. Magendran and Datuk N. Mohanadas climbed Mount Everest; Datuk Abdul Malik Mydin swam across the English Channel [...] People cheered these plucky Malaysians and saw their achievements as, if not world-beating, at least world-class.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mohamad |first1=Mahathir |title=A doctor in the house: The momoirs of Tun Dr Mahathir Mohamad |date=2011 |publisher=MPH Group |location=Selangor |isbn=978-967-5997-22-8 |page=843 |edition=3rd}}</ref>}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* On 29 May 2003, M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas (the only two Mount Everest summiteers from Malaysia) received the Mount Everest Golden jubilee Medals from the Honourable Prime Minister of Nepal, [[Lokendra Bahadur Chand]]. Both were invited by the [[Nepal Mountaineering Association]] (NMA) to be a part of the week-long celebration organized by the [[Nepal]] Government in conjunction with the 50th Anniversary of the conquest of Mount Everest in 1953.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/986791/Nepal-marks-50th-anniversary-of-Mount-Everest-climb.html|title=Nepal marks 50th Anniversary of Mount Everest climb|author=Laurinda Keys|newspaper=Deseret News|date=30 May 2003|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2003-05-26/everest-golden-jubilee-celebrations-kick-off/1859364|title=Everest golden jubilee celebrations kick off|publisher=ABC News|date=25 May 2003|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n* On 10 July 2010, M. Magendran was among 47 people who were conferred the Darjah Setia Pangkuan Negeri award (DSPN),<ref name=\"DSPN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/07/11/mt-everest-climbers-happy-to-get-recognition-for-their-feat/|title=On top of the world again - Mt. Everest climbers happy to get recognition for their feat|author=Manjit Kaur|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 June 2019}}</ref> which carries the title [[Datuk#Datuk|Datuk]] in conjunction with the 72nd birthday of the Penang [[Yang di-Pertua Negeri|State Governor]] [[Tun Abdul Rahman Abbas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/07/10/mt-everest-climbers-get-datukships/|title=Mt Everest climbers get Datukships |author=K.Suthakar|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 June 2019}}</ref> Magendran was honoured along with team mate N. Mohanadas.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/06/04/a-mountain-of-memories/|title=A mountain of memories |author=Shahanaaz Habib |publisher=The Star |date=4 June 2017|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref> Second Deputy Chief Minister of Penang Prof. Dr. [[Ramasamy Palanisamy]]<ref name=\"DSPN\"/>   said the state government gave the awards to the duo to recognize their feat.\n* On 4 June 2011, M. Magendran was honoured with the Distinguished Order of Meritorious Service (Darjah Panglima Jasa Negara) or [[Order of Meritorious Service|PJN]]<ref>{{ cite web|url=  https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2011/06/05/abdullah-ayub-among-1707-conferred-titles-in-conjunction-with-kings-birthday/|title=Abdullah  Ayub among 1707 conferred titles in conjunction with king\u2019s birthday |publisher=The Star|date=5 June 2011|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> in conjunction with the birthday of [[Yang Di-Pertuan Agong|His Majesty]]  [[Tuanku Mizan Zainal Abidin]],<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2011/06/04/list-of-award-recipients-in-conjunction-with-kings-birthday/|title=List of award recipients in conjunction with king\u2019s birthday|publisher=The Star|date=4 June 2011|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> the 13th King of Malaysia. Magendran was among 67 people who were conferred the PJN award which carries the tilte [[Datuk#Datuk|Datuk]].\n* On 23 May 2017, Both M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas together with other team members of Malaysia-Everest 97 expedition were honoured in an event \u201cTwo decades of first Malaysians on Everest\u201d organised by The Malaysian Indian Sports and Cultural Foundation (MISCF)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2014/07/25/a-boost-for-malaysian-indian-athletes-sports-ministry-welcomes-formation-of-miscf/|title=A boost for Malaysian Indian Athletes|author=Y.P. Sivam|publisher=The Star|date= 25 July 2014|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref> and [[Ministry of Youth and Sports (Malaysia)]] to commemorate the 20th anniversary of their historic feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/community/2017/05/30/mt-everest-conquerors-20-years-on-ministry-and-sports-foundation-honour-magendran-mohanadas-and-the/|title=Mt Everest conquerors 20 years on|author=Y.P. Sivam|publisher=The Star|date= 30 May 2017|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.utusan.com.my/berita/nasional/genap-20-tahun-tawan-everest-1.485556 |title=Genap 20 tahun tawan Everest|author=R. Umavathi|newspaper=Utusan Malaysia|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n[[File:The Malaysian Federal Honour - Panglima Jasa Negara (PJN).jpg|thumb|M. Magendran at the [[Istana Melawati]], Putrajaya after receiving the Panglima Jasa Negara (PJN) award (2011)]]\n\n=== Honours of Malaysia ===\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:MY Darjah Jasa Negara - Order of Meritorious Service - PJN.svg|50px]]Commander of the [[Order of Meritorious Service]] (PJN) - '''Datuk'''(2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-star-malaysia/20110608/textview |publisher=The Star|date=8 June 2011|title=Yang Di-Pertuan Agong's Birthday Honours List|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n**[[File: Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - SSM.svg|50px]] Companion of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (JSM) (2004)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\">{{cite web|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n** [[File:MY Darjah Yang Mulia Pangkuan Negara (Defender of the Realm) - SMN.svg|50px]] Officer of the [[Order of the Defender of the Realm#Officer|Order of the Defender of the Realm]] (KMN) (1997)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\"/>\n* {{Flag|Penang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PEN Order of the Defender of State - Officer - DSPN.svg|50px]] Officer of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|Order of the Defender of State]] (DSPN) - '''Datuk''' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com |title= On top of the world again - Mt. Everest climbers happy to get recognition for their feat|author=Manjit Kaur|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 June 2019}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Selangor}} :\n**[[File:MY-SEL Order of the Crown of Selangor - Knight Grand Commander - SPMS.svg|50px]] Member of the [[Order of the Crown of Selangor#Member|Order of the Crown of Selangor]] (AMS) (1999)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of climbers and mountaineers]]\n* [[List of Malaysians#Others|List of notable Malaysians]]\n* [[List of Tamil people#Mountain climbing|List of notable Tamil people]]\n* [[Timeline of climbing Mount Everest#1997|Timeline of climbing Mount Everest \u2013 1997]]\n\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rahman |first1=Abdul Aziz |title=100 Wira Negara |date=2012 |publisher=Majlis Bekas Wakil Rakyat Malaysia (MUBARAK) |location=Kuala Lumpur |isbn=978-967-10541-0-9 |page=301 |edition=First |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ahmad |first1=Norlaila |title=Memori Pejuang Bangsa: Bersama mencipta masa depan gemilang |date=2008 |publisher=Jabatan Penerangan Malaysia |location=Kuala Lumpur |isbn=978-983--5405-32-7 |page=399 |edition=First |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Mohamad |first1=Mahathir |title=A doctor in the house: The momoirs of Tun Dr Mahathir Mohamad |date=2011 |publisher=MPH Group |location=Selangor |isbn=978-967-5997-22-8 |page=843 |edition=3rd}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084659/http://en.netlog.com/datukmmagendran M. Magendran on Netlog]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/datuk.magendran?fref=ts&ref=br_tf M. Magendran's Facebook page]\n* https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-star-malaysia/20110608/textview\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magendran, M.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Hindus]]\n[[Category:Malaysian mountain climbers]]\n[[Category:Summiters of Mount Everest]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Datuk\n| name               = M. Magendran\n| image              = M. Magendran Everest, Nepal 1997.jpg\n| caption            = M. Magendran on the summit of Mount Everest - 23 May 1997\n| native_name        = \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd. \u0bae\u0b95\u0bc7\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba9\u0bcd\n| native_name_lang   = [[Tamil language]]\n| birth_name         = Magendran M. Munisamy\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|6 December 1963}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = * {{Flag|Malaysia}} :  Malaysian\n| education          = M. Ed,<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Malaya Theses and Dissertations|url=http://www.diglib.um.edu.my/umtheses/browse.asp?page=31&level=all&faculty=P&year=all#sthash.F6yYG5vC.dpbs}}</ref> [[University of Malaya]], Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. \nB. Sp. Sc  (Hons), University of Malaya, Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.\n| spouse             = [[Malay title#Datin|Datin]] V. Senthamarai<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/07/11/mt-everest-climbers-happy-to-get-recognition-for-their-feat/|title= On top of the world again - Mt. Everest climbers happy to get recognition for their feat|author=Manjit Kaur|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 August 2019}}</ref> \n| children           = 3\n| occupation         = Teacher / Sports Manager<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/sport/other-sport/2013/04/18/german-stint-for-rayzam-and-hup-wei/|title=German stint for Rayzam and Hup Wei|publisher=The Star|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/sport/athletics/2015/02/27/lee-hup-wei-might-miss-sea-games-again/|title=High jumper Hup Wei might miss SEA Games again |author=Aftar Singh|newspaper=The Star Online|date=27 February 2015|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> \n| known_for          = * First [[Malaysians|Malaysian]]/[[Tamil people|Tamil]] to conquer [[Mount Everest]]\n* The Malaysian title of [[Malay titles#Datuk|Datuk]]\n* Photo on postage stamp<ref name=\"Random\" /><ref name=\"thebrandlaureate.net\">{{cite web|title=Datuk M Magendran - The first Malaysian Mount Everest summiteer|url=http://thebrandlaureate.net/2016/10/25/datuk-m-magendran/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Millenium Series III - Spirit of New Malaysian|url=https://myfdc.me/malaysia-first-day-covers/1991-2000/2000-2/|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Siri Milenium III - Semangat Malaysia Baru|url=http://sampulfdc.blogspot.com/2010/11/siri-milenium-iii-semangat-malaysia.html|accessdate= 6 August 2019}}</ref>\n}}<!-- [[wp:COMMONNAME]] is by far \"M. Magendran\", so that is the correct title of this article.  P. Ellsworth, ed. -->\n[[Malay title#Datuk|Datuk]] '''M. Magendran''' [[Order of Meritorious Service|PJN]] [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|DSPN]] [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia|JSM]] [[Order of the Defender of the Realm#Officer|KMN]] [[List of post-nominal letters (Selangor)|AMS]] ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd. \u0bae\u0b95\u0bc7\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba9\u0bcd) born '''Magendran M. Munisamy'''<ref name=\"Messner\">{{cite book |title=Everest: Expedition to the Ultimate |author=Reinhold Messner |authorlink=Reinhold Messner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E4Tf5tL407EC&pg=PA256&dq=%22Magendran%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LbHqUbb1MIiI9ATQ6YGAAg&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Magendran%22&f=false |publisher=The Mountaineers Books |year=1999 |page=256 |isbn=0-89886-648-0 |accessdate=20 July 2013}}</ref> on\n6 December 1963<ref name=\"thebrandlaureate.net\">{{cite web|title=Datuk M Magendran - The first Malaysian Mount Everest summiteer|url=http://thebrandlaureate.net/2016/10/25/datuk-m-magendran/}}</ref>   in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]) is the first Malaysian [[mountain climber]] and first [[Tamil people|Tamil]] to conquer the summit of [[Mount Everest]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Malaysia's Everest Quest |url=http://www.hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=5023 |date=1 September 1997 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923050944/http://hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=5023 |archivedate=23 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mountaineering |author=Khalid Yunus |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com.my/volume15/138.html |publisher=encyclopedia.com |work=The Encyclopedia of Malaysia |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617233929/http://www.encyclopedia.com.my/volume15/138.html |archivedate=17 June 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Magendran's party ascended the [[South Col]] on the [[Mount Everest#Southeast ridge|southeast ridge]].<ref name=\"Messner\" /> He stepped onto Everest's summit on 23 May 1997, at 11:55&nbsp;a.m. local time. He was followed by N. Mohanadas (Mohanadas Nagappan), who reached the summit a few minutes later at 12:10&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Best Records of the Year |url=http://www.malaysiarecords.com.my/recordoftheyear.php |author=The Malaysia Book of Records |authorlink=Malaysian Book of Records |publisher=Malaysiarecords.com.my |year=1995\u20132012 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020100436/http://www.malaysiarecords.com.my/recordoftheyear.php |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mount Everest Expedition |author=Sambutan Kemerdekaan |url=http://www.malaysiamerdeka.gov.my/v2/en/achievements/271-pendakian-gunung-everest |publisher=Malaysiamerdeka.gov.my |year=1997 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518080052/http://www.malaysiamerdeka.gov.my/v2/en/achievements/271-pendakian-gunung-everest |archivedate=18 May 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two [[mountaineer]]s were part of the first \"Malaysia-Everest Project 97\" jointly organised by the Malaysia Mountaineering Association and the [[Ministry of Youth and Sports (Malaysia)|Ministry of Youth and Sports of Malaysia]].  Also with their team of ten people was [[M. Moorthy]] (Moorthy Maniam), a Malaysian of [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] descent.\n\nMount Everest is the world's highest mountain, with a peak at 8,848 metres (29,029&nbsp;ft) above sea level. Its summit was first achieved in 1953 after numerous failed attempts that began in 1921. The first person to finally set foot on its summit was [[New Zealand]]er Sir [[Edmund Hillary]], who was accompanied by [[Tenzing Norgay]] of [[India]].  Both M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas were conferred [[Malay titles#Datuk|Datukships]] by the [[Penang]] state government in 2010 for their [[Himalaya]]n achievement.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mt Everest climbers get Datukships |author=K. Suthakar |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/story.aspx?file=%2f2010%2f7%2f10%2fnation%2f6637881&sec=nation |newspaper=[[The Star Online]] |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020120903/http://www.thestar.com.my/story.aspx?file=%2f2010%2f7%2f10%2fnation%2f6637881&sec=nation |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two ethnic Indians receive Malaysia's Datukship title |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/two-ethnic-indians-receive-malaysias-datukship-title/645271/ |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=12 July 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref> Both men were also conferred the Federal 'Datukships' title by the King of Malaysia in Jun 2011 [http://www.thestar.com.my/story.aspx/?file=%2F2011%2F6%2F5%2Fnation%2F8842050&sec=nation]\n\nIn June 2013, Datuk Magendran, who is considered a pioneer among Malaysians, gave advice for those mountain climbers who would brave the hazards of the world's highest peak:\n{{quote|ALL safety and preparatory efforts must be taken before setting out on a mountain climb, especially when it involves the world's tallest mountain.  One should be ''very well prepared'' and must have undergone rigorous physical and mental training before taking on the mammoth peak, [...] One must undergo sufficient training and preparation, which includes endurance training and altitude training.  I had been involved in outdoor activities such as mountain climbing and jungle-trekking for ten years and received almost three years of rigorous training before our team left for Mount Everest in 1997.<ref name=\"newstraits\">{{Cite news |title=Safety key to Everest ascent |author=Kalbana Perimbanayagam and Hashini Kavishtri Kannan |url=http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/safety-key-to-everest-ascent-1.297890 |publisher=[[New Straits Times Online]] |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=17 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616125658/http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/safety-key-to-everest-ascent-1.297890 |archivedate=16 June 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}\n\nMagendran urged future climbers and trekkers not to overlook their health before and during the climb, adding that any symptom that was overlooked could be fatal.  He also reminded, \"Trekkers should keep an eye on the health of their teammates, too.\"<ref name=\"newstraits\" />\n\nThe year 1997 also commemorated the 40th anniversary of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaysian independence]].<ref name=\"am002\">The UK Statute Law Database: [http://www.statutelaw.gov.uk/content.aspx?LegType=All%20Primary&PageNumber=72&NavFrom=2&parentActiveTextDocId=1118475&ActiveTextDocId=1118475&filesize=15776 Federation of Malaya Independence Act 1957 (c. 60)]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved 19 July 2013</ref> In 2000, both M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas were pictured on their nation's postage stamps.[http://sampulfdc.blogspot.com/2010/11/siri-milenium-iii-semangat-malaysia.html]<ref name=\"Random\">{{Cite book |title=Malaysia at Random |series=At Random Series |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5VvvOi9mRHIC&pg=PA75&dq=%22M.+Magendran%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eaXqUd7gIIrW9ATCkIHADQ&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA |publisher=[[Editions Didier Millet]] |page=75 |year=2010 |isbn=9814217956 |accessdate=20 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nMagendran is a vice-principal in SMK USJ 8, in Subang Jaya. Being a Sports Science and Physical Education graduate, he also teaches Physical Education.<ref name=\"The Star Online 2017\">{{cite web |website=The Star Online |date=4 June 2017| title=Still feeling on top of the world |author=Shahanaaz Habib|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/06/04/still-feeling-on-top-of-the-world-twenty-years-ago-malaysia-made-history-when-m-magendran-and-n-moha/ |access-date=3 June 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018073830/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/06/04/still-feeling-on-top-of-the-world-twenty-years-ago-malaysia-made-history-when-m-magendran-and-n-moha/ |archivedate=18 October 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 (Malaysia Can Do It!) ==\n[[File:Malaysian Everest `97 - Official logo.jpg|thumb|The official logo of the first Malaysian Everest Expedition (Malaysia-Everest `97)]]\n\nThe idea of `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 was first mooted in 1993 by [[Nestle]] and made its debut as part of a marketing campaign for [[Milo (drink)]], and a confidence boost for the Malaysian contingent during the 1993 [[Southeast Asia Games]] in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://says.com/my/lifestyle/the-origin-of-the-slogan-malaysia-boleh |title=Did you know:The iconic `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 Slogan originated from a marketing campaign|author=Samantha Khor |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref>\nThe`Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 slogan slowly gained influence as a signature battle cry in the mid 90\u2019s when Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad]] co-opted the catch phrase to spur the nation's [[Wawasan 2020|Vision 2020]]. Likewise, the Malaysia-Everest `97 organizing committee also incorporated the phrase to its official expedition logo to instill a sense of confidence and perseverance among the climbers. And the force of the slogan worked both ways, it gave the climbers the competitive spirit to strive for excellence and the success of the expedition gave the much needed oomph to the `Malaysia Boleh! spirit. The slogan became more popular and inspired many Malaysians to embark on other adventures like the Read brothers who walked to the last degree of the North pole (1998), Dato' [[Azhar Mansor]] who sailed solo around the world (1999), Dato' [[Abdul Malik Mydin]] who swam across the English Channel (2003) and many more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/travel/malaysia/2011/04/06/malaysia-boleh/|title=Malaysia Boleh |author=Maf73 |publisher=The Star |date=6 April 2011|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebrandlaureate.net/2016/10/25/datuk-m-magendran/|title=M. Magendran- The first Malaysian Mount  Everest Summiteer}}</ref>\nThe stories of these exemplary Malaysians never cease to amaze the Prime Minister whenever he speaks about discipline, patience and over-coming challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/08/31/pm-discipline-and-patience-are-also-vital/|title=PM:Discipline and patience are also vital|publisher=The Star|date=31 August 2003|accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref> Tun Dr. [[Mahathir Mohamad]] in his book, A Doctor in the House: The Memoirs of Tun Dr. Mahathir Mohamad (pg. 589) stated that:\n{{quote|The new `Malaysia Boleh!\u2019 (Malaysia can do it) seemed to take hold and coincide with the period of growth. [[The Malaysia Book of Records]] had also been started and people now try to pull off unusual feat to get into it. The new competitive spirit, combined with the desire to show that Malaysians could do anything, generated much excitement in the country. Datuk Azhar Mansor sailed solo around the world; Datuk M. Magendran and Datuk N. Mohanadas climbed Mount Everest; Datuk Abdul Malik Mydin swam across the English Channel [...] People cheered these plucky Malaysians and saw their achievements as, if not world-beating, at least world-class.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mohamad |first1=Mahathir |title=A doctor in the house: The momoirs of Tun Dr Mahathir Mohamad |date=2011 |publisher=MPH Group |location=Selangor |isbn=978-967-5997-22-8 |page=843 |edition=3rd}}</ref>}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* On 29 May 2003, M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas (the only two Mount Everest summiteers from Malaysia) received the Mount Everest Golden jubilee Medals from the Honourable Prime Minister of Nepal, [[Lokendra Bahadur Chand]]. Both were invited by the [[Nepal Mountaineering Association]] (NMA) to be a part of the week-long celebration organized by the [[Nepal]] Government in conjunction with the 50th Anniversary of the conquest of Mount Everest in 1953.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/986791/Nepal-marks-50th-anniversary-of-Mount-Everest-climb.html|title=Nepal marks 50th Anniversary of Mount Everest climb|author=Laurinda Keys|newspaper=Deseret News|date=30 May 2003|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2003-05-26/everest-golden-jubilee-celebrations-kick-off/1859364|title=Everest golden jubilee celebrations kick off|publisher=ABC News|date=25 May 2003|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n* On 10 July 2010, M. Magendran was among 47 people who were conferred the Darjah Setia Pangkuan Negeri award (DSPN),<ref name=\"DSPN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/07/11/mt-everest-climbers-happy-to-get-recognition-for-their-feat/|title=On top of the world again - Mt. Everest climbers happy to get recognition for their feat|author=Manjit Kaur|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 June 2019}}</ref> which carries the title [[Datuk#Datuk|Datuk]] in conjunction with the 72nd birthday of the Penang [[Yang di-Pertua Negeri|State Governor]] [[Tun Abdul Rahman Abbas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/07/10/mt-everest-climbers-get-datukships/|title=Mt Everest climbers get Datukships |author=K.Suthakar|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 June 2019}}</ref> Magendran was honoured along with team mate N. Mohanadas.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/06/04/a-mountain-of-memories/|title=A mountain of memories |author=Shahanaaz Habib |publisher=The Star |date=4 June 2017|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref> Second Deputy Chief Minister of Penang Prof. Dr. [[Ramasamy Palanisamy]]<ref name=\"DSPN\"/>   said the state government gave the awards to the duo to recognize their feat.\n* On 4 June 2011, M. Magendran was honoured with the Distinguished Order of Meritorious Service (Darjah Panglima Jasa Negara) or [[Order of Meritorious Service|PJN]]<ref>{{ cite web|url=  https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2011/06/05/abdullah-ayub-among-1707-conferred-titles-in-conjunction-with-kings-birthday/|title=Abdullah  Ayub among 1707 conferred titles in conjunction with king\u2019s birthday |publisher=The Star|date=5 June 2011|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> in conjunction with the birthday of [[Yang Di-Pertuan Agong|His Majesty]]  [[Tuanku Mizan Zainal Abidin]],<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2011/06/04/list-of-award-recipients-in-conjunction-with-kings-birthday/|title=List of award recipients in conjunction with king\u2019s birthday|publisher=The Star|date=4 June 2011|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> the 13th King of Malaysia. Magendran was among 67 people who were conferred the PJN award which carries the tilte [[Datuk#Datuk|Datuk]].\n* On 23 May 2017, Both M. Magendran and N. Mohanadas together with other team members of Malaysia-Everest 97 expedition were honoured in an event \u201cTwo decades of first Malaysians on Everest\u201d organised by The Malaysian Indian Sports and Cultural Foundation (MISCF)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2014/07/25/a-boost-for-malaysian-indian-athletes-sports-ministry-welcomes-formation-of-miscf/|title=A boost for Malaysian Indian Athletes|author=Y.P. Sivam|publisher=The Star|date= 25 July 2014|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref> and [[Ministry of Youth and Sports (Malaysia)]] to commemorate the 20th anniversary of their historic feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/community/2017/05/30/mt-everest-conquerors-20-years-on-ministry-and-sports-foundation-honour-magendran-mohanadas-and-the/|title=Mt Everest conquerors 20 years on|author=Y.P. Sivam|publisher=The Star|date= 30 May 2017|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.utusan.com.my/berita/nasional/genap-20-tahun-tawan-everest-1.485556 |title=Genap 20 tahun tawan Everest|author=R. Umavathi|newspaper=Utusan Malaysia|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n[[File:The Malaysian Federal Honour - Panglima Jasa Negara (PJN).jpg|thumb|M. Magendran at the [[Istana Melawati]], Putrajaya after receiving the Panglima Jasa Negara (PJN) award (2011)]]\n\n=== Honours of Malaysia ===\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:MY Darjah Jasa Negara - Order of Meritorious Service - PJN.svg|50px]]Commander of the [[Order of Meritorious Service]] (PJN) - '''Datuk'''(2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-star-malaysia/20110608/textview |publisher=The Star|date=8 June 2011|title=Yang Di-Pertuan Agong's Birthday Honours List|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n**[[File: Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - SSM.svg|50px]] Companion of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (JSM) (2004)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\">{{cite web|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n** [[File:MY Darjah Yang Mulia Pangkuan Negara (Defender of the Realm) - SMN.svg|50px]] Officer of the [[Order of the Defender of the Realm#Officer|Order of the Defender of the Realm]] (KMN) (1997)<ref name=\"istiadat.gov.my\"/>\n* {{Flag|Penang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PEN Order of the Defender of State - Officer - DSPN.svg|50px]] Officer of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|Order of the Defender of State]] (DSPN) - '''Datuk''' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com |title= On top of the world again - Mt. Everest climbers happy to get recognition for their feat|author=Manjit Kaur|publisher=The Star|date=11 July 2010|accessdate= 6 June 2019}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Selangor}} :\n**[[File:MY-SEL Order of the Crown of Selangor - Knight Grand Commander - SPMS.svg|50px]] Member of the [[Order of the Crown of Selangor#Member|Order of the Crown of Selangor]] (AMS) (1999)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of climbers and mountaineers]]\n* [[List of Malaysians#Others|List of notable Malaysians]]\n* [[List of Tamil people#Mountain climbing|List of notable Tamil people]]\n* [[Timeline of climbing Mount Everest#1997|Timeline of climbing Mount Everest \u2013 1997]]\n\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rahman |first1=Abdul Aziz |title=100 Wira Negara |date=2012 |publisher=Majlis Bekas Wakil Rakyat Malaysia (MUBARAK) |location=Kuala Lumpur |isbn=978-967-10541-0-9 |page=301 |edition=First |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ahmad |first1=Norlaila |title=Memori Pejuang Bangsa: Bersama mencipta masa depan gemilang |date=2008 |publisher=Jabatan Penerangan Malaysia |location=Kuala Lumpur |isbn=978-983--5405-32-7 |page=399 |edition=First |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{